<HEADLINE> China Stabilizer Of Financial Situation  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Because of the combined effect of the surplus and net capital
influx in the capital account, the yuan has experienced
appreciation pressure in the last several years, Bottelier
explained.
</P>
<P>
A strong currency and a high amount of foreign reserves in
relation to imports and short-term debt also helped to keep China
unaffected by the financial crisis that has engulfed Indonesia,
the Philippines, Malaysia, the Republic of Korea, Hong Kong, and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the origin of the crisis in China's
neighboring countries underscores the urgent need for China to
increase supervision over all its financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
"Although China is relatively well insulated from the crisis,
there is no room for complacency," Bottelier said, and a slowdown
in exports and reduced foreign investment must be anticipated in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
To protect the country from possible economic difficulties in
future and to sustain the reforms and modernization, China should
accelerate reforms in state-owned enterprises and the
commercialization of the state banks, as was decided by the 15th
Party Congress and the State Council, he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
