<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Air Cargo Throughput Hits Record High in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The volume of air cargo
throughput which passed through Hong Kong's Kai Tak airport
reached a record high of some 1.7 million tons in 1997, the air
cargo operator, Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals Ltd. (HACTL),
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,695,127 tons of air freight passed through HACTL's
cargo complex during the year. Courier traffic and commercial
goods carried in baggage handled through the complex amounted to a
further 28,233 tons, taking the overall tonnage to 1,723,360.
</P>
<P>
Final figures show that HACTL surpassed the million-ton mark
back in August and since then has maintained a strong performance
with three new monthly records set during September, October and
November, resulting in a tonnage growth of 13.8 percent for the
year.
</P>
<P>
"It has truly been a good year in every respect. Since the
start of 1997, the growth in air cargo has outpaced our
forecasts," commented HACTL Managing Director Anthony Charter.
</P>
<P>
Kai Tak overtook Tokyo's Narita Airport in 1996 for the first
time to become the world's biggest airport in terms of
international cargo.
</P>
<P>
"With a growth rate of 13.8 percent and in view of the slower
economy in Japan over the past year, it is very likely that Kai
Tak will again rank first in this league of airports," Charter
said.
</P>
<P>
Over 14 million tons of air freight have been managed by the
air cargo operator since it commenced operation in Hong Kong 22
years ago. Five months away it will move to SuperTerminal 1 at the
Chek Lap Kok new airport, which is due to open on July 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
