<HEADLINE> Increasing Cooperation Between Shenzhen, Hong Kong's Customs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Cooperation between customs
officers in Shenzhen, in China's Guangdong Province, and nearby
Hong Kong will be increased to improve economic ties between Hong
Kong and the rest of China.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Mayor Li Decheng revealed this at a conference of
ministerial department officials today on reforming customs work
in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Shenzhen customs office will try to improve
the ties with joint inspections, improved office conditions, and
new customs facilities. The reforms will make Shenzhen customs
closer to Hong Kong customs in work methods to improve future
cooperation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, Shenzhen was the first city in China to have
customs office reforms and these have made it much more efficient.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Shenzhen customs handled 73.29 million people, 8.83
million vehicles, and 46.36 million tons of goods, up 15.9
percent, 3.4 percent and 7.5 percent year-on-year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Shenzhen Port handled 1.14 million TEUs, an increase
of 94.1 percent, making it the country's second largest container
port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
