<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Airlines, Couriers Ignore Hazardous Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. airlines and courier
services do not strictly follow the required security procedures
designed to detect dangerous cargo despite repeated warnings, a
government report said.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) conducted inspections
of airlines and courier services in New York and Miami and found
that the current level of compliance with approved security
procedures was unacceptably low.
</P>
<P>
Security was so lax that 10 suitcases loaded with 50 pounds
each of pesticide slipped by airline personnel undetected in Miami
three months ago and were not discovered until one burst as it was
being loaded onto a plane, the FAA said in a report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In May 1996, a ValuJet plane crashed in the Florida Everglades,
killing all 110 people on board. Investigators believe poorly
packaged oxygen canisters ignited or fueled a fire that caused the
crash.
</P>
<P>
Even one year after the accident, seven oxygen generators were
shipped aboard a Continental Airlines flight in violation of rules
imposed after the ValuJet crash.
</P>
<P>
The FAA has made rules for years that require air cargo
companies and courier services, which deliver packages to the
commercial airlines for shipment, to certify that bags or packages
do not contain any explosives or hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
Airlines are also required to demand to see the documentation
before loading the cargo.
</P>
<P>
But in a test at the Miami Airport in October, inspectors found
10 of the 17 courier services were willing to accept packages from
shippers they had not dealt with previously, but none of the 10
followed the security procedures. Also, none of the 13 airlines
that agreed to carry the packages followed the procedures, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
In a test at the New York John F. Kennedy Airport in November,
inspectors found that two of the 11 courier services and five of
the 21 air carriers failed to follow the FAA rules.
</P>
<P>
In response to the findings, the FAA issued a strict warning to
airlines and courier services that transport cargo or baggage on
airlines for customers.
</P>
<P>
The FAA also said it was considering additional procedures to
prohibit luggage or cargo from carrying onto planes without check.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
