<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis to Reduce Canada's Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing crisis in Asian
economies has forced some Canadian economists to reduce their
predictions for the country's economic growth this year.
</P>
<P>
In its latest annual forecast, economists at the Canadian
Imperial Bank of Commerce (CIBC) predict that Canada's economy
will grow 3.3 percent this year, down from the 3.5 percent
forecast earlier.
</P>
<P>
The present forecast could be further revised downward if the
Asian crisis worsens, said Joshua Mendelsohn, chief economist of
the CIBC, Canada's second largest commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
In a similar move, the Bank of Nova Scotia said it was reducing
its economic growth forecast to 3 percent from 4 percent in
November.
</P>
<P>
Warren Jestin, Nova Scotia's chief economist, said the real
impact of Asia problems will not begin to show up in Canada's
trade performance and in the profits of Canadian companies for
another few months.
</P>
<P>
When it does, there will be a lot of earnings surprises, the
economist warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
