<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Farmers Seek to Reduce AIDS Menace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Farmers Union
today held a one-day AIDS workshop here to deliberate on the
impact of HIV/AIDS on the agricultural sector and seek ways to
reduce the AIDS menace.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 delegates from the communal farming sector are
attending the workshop which aims to identify strategies of
coping with HIV/AIDS in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Some 13 years after the first case was identified in Zimbabwe,
HIV infection is still spreading at an alarming rate with 67,198
cumulative cases having been reported up to June last year.
</P>
<P>
Coordinator of the Zimbabwean National AIDS Coordination
Program Everisto Marowa said today at the workshop, ''It is
estimated that more than 1.4 million people have been infected
with HIV while a cumulative total of more than 300,000 cases of
full blown AIDS had occurred since the beginning of the
epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
With dozens of non-governmental organizations having been
established to help the 12.5 million population deal with the
pandemic, HIV related illnesses account for more than 50 percent
of the country's bed occupancy in health institutions.
</P>
<P>
Rapid spread of the virus and subsequent illness and death has
resulted in lowered productivity levels due to high absentism.
</P>
<P>
''The overall objective of the workshop is to find an action
plan of how to deal with this from a farming perspective,''
Deputy Director of the Zimbabwe Farmers Union Emmerson Zhou said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
