<HEADLINE> London Gold, Silver Clearing Hits Records in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The average daily clearing
turnover for gold and silver in London both hit records in
December, the Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures from the London Bullion Market Association, the
newspaper said that the average daily volume of gold cleared in
London, the international settlement center for gold bullion, was
43.7 million troy ounces, the highest level recorded since
statistics began in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the fall of gold price to the lowest level for
18 years, the value of daily turnover was only at 12.6 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure was well below the record of 14 billion dollars seen
in February 1997 although it was slightly up on the 12.5 billion
dollars a day cleared in November when the average daily volume
was 40.8 million ounces.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the association said that the volume of silver
cleared daily last month was also at the highest level it has yet
recorded, as was the daily value.
</P>
<P>
The volume and value of silver cleared daily were at 395.8
million troy ounces and 2.3 billion dollars respectively, compared
with the previous records of a daily volume of 345.5 million
ounces set in October 1997 and a value of 1.7 billion dollars
recorded in both October and November last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
