<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Customs Seizes 24 Smuggled Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Customs officers
seized 24 smuggled left-hand drive vehicles worth about 10 million
HK dollars (1.3 million U.S. dollars) Wednesday, the Customs and
Excise Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The brand-new vehicles, 13 Japanese made and 11 German made,
were found inside six containers after the officers intercepted a
vessel conveying 14 40-foot loaded containers to Shantou,
Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
The left-hand drive vehicles, being prohibited articles and
controlled under the Import and Export Ordinance, were not covered
by any valid export license.
</P>
<P>
Initial inquires led to the arrest of three men, aged between
25 and 39, suspected of exporting the seized shipment. The crew of
the vessel were released to continue their voyage after the
officers found that they were not involved in the smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Under the Import and Export Ordinance, any person who is
convicted of "attempting to export prohibited article without a
license" will be liable to a maximum penalty of a fine of 2
million HK dollars (256,000 U.S. dollars) and imprisonment of
seven years.
</P>
<P>
This is the second left-hand drive vehicle smuggling case
detected by Customs this year. In 1997, Customs seized 170
left-hand drive vehicles and arrested 42 persons in 32 cases. The
seizure value amounted to 95.5 million HK dollars (12.2 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
