<HEADLINE> Meles Calls for Religious Tolerance in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi today said Moslems and Christians have lived
together for centuries in Ethiopia with love and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by the Ethiopian premier when he
received and held talks with Ishmael Noko, Secretary General of
the Lutheran World Federation.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Ethiopian News Agency, Meles
said, freedom of worship is one of the provisions enshrined in
the constitution of Ethiopia and has been implemented
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
He said, religious tolerance has been a long standing
tradition of Ethiopians.
</P>
<P>
Meles told the visiting guest that his government has returned
properties which were nationalized under the previous regime.
</P>
<P>
He said, the prevalence of peace is decisive for
democratization and development to gain momentum, adding that the
church could play a key role in the effort to restore peace in
the continent.
</P>
<P>
While peace has been prevailing in the southern part of
Africa, there is yet much to be done in this respect in the Horn
and the Great Lakes region, Meles said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Noko said on his part that the
federation is grateful to the Ethiopian government for its
positive attitudes toward church operations.
</P>
<P>
Noko said that he is closely following the democratization
process in Ethiopia and urged the continuation of efforts by
Prime Minister Meles for the restoration of peace and stability
in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The Lutheran World Federation has played a decisive role for
the restoration of peace in different parts of the world, Noko
said, adding that it supports the effort to bring about peace and
stability in the Horn of Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
