<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Confident to Overcome Temporary Difficulties: Tung (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa said
Thursday that he believed the SAR will be the first to get back on
its feet after the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a question-and-answer session of the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC), Tung told members of the PLC: "We have
no reason to lose confidence of ourselves, nor have we any ground
to believe that Hong Kong will never be able to scale new
heights."
</P>
<P>
The problem Hong Kong is now facing is nothing but to find the
way to overcome the temporary difficulties and keep moving ahead
to reach new heights.
</P>
<P>
In the face of this financial situation, the SAR government's
most important task at hand is to take firm and resolute measures
to safeguard the stability of Hong Kong's economic system, Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this, it is vital for the SAR to defend the linked
exchange rate between the Hong Kong dollar and the U.S. dollar,
and the SAR government is determined to do so.
</P>
<P>
This is a basic policy to maintain Hong Kong's economic
stability and prosperity, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will succeed in defending the linked exchange rate
due to its sound economic foundation, huge fiscal reserves and
effective financial system and monitoring mechanism, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"The staggering events in some Asian countries have only served
to strengthen our determination to maintain the linkage. Failure
to do so will bring disastrous consequences," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Confident to Overcome Temporary Difficulties: Tung (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the course of defending the linked exchange rate system, the
interest rate of the HK dollar goes up; property prices come down;
the stock market lingers at low levels; tourism is in the
doldrums; the consumer spending sentiment diminishes; Hong Kong's
economic growth in 1998 will slow down and unemployment figures
will be on the rise, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
If the external uncertainties do not clear up as soon as
possible, there will be difficult times for all of the Hong Kong
people in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government is well aware of the sufferings and problems
encountered by the people in the current financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
However, the economic adjustment that comes as a result of the
recent financial turmoil has certain positive effects on Hong
Kong's economy, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
He listed the effects as the decline of property prices and the
slow-down of salary adjustment and inflation, which will enhance
Hong Kong's competitiveness and be conducive to the long-term
healthy economic development of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We maintain a very optimistic attitude towards Hong Kong's
inherent strengths as well as its resilience in adapting itself to
unfavorable circumstances," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The forecast of the relevant government department reveals that
Hong Kong's economy will continue to grow in 1998 despite the
marked economic slow-down in the city, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We should remember in particular that upon the smooth return
of Hong Kong to China on July 1, 1997, we have become masters of
our own home," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Government has great confidence in Hong Kong and
believes that the Hong Kong people is able to administer Hong Kong
properly under the principle of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
"Given the trust of the Central Government as well as that of
the entire nation, there is no reason for us not to trust
ourselves," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Tung expressed his hope that the SAR government, the PLC
members and the whole community will work together to build a
harmonious and cooperative society to surmount difficulties in
adverse situation and to rise to challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Confident to Overcome Temporary Difficulties: Tung (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the session, the chief executive answered questions from
the PLC members.
</P>
<P>
Asked to predict the growth rate of Hong Kong in 1998, Tung
said that Hong Kong would see four percent growth in gross
domestic product (GDP) despite Asia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The growth will not be zero or negative," Tung said. But this
depends largely on external factors, he added.
</P>
<P>
Some PLC members concerned that the maintenance of the peg will
reduce Hong Kong's competitiveness as other countries and regions
in Asia have devalued their currencies.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that what is important now is to create a good
investment environment and regain the confidence of investors. He
believed investors will not leave Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Some PLC members also raised questions about such issues as
avian flu and environmental hygiene and using mother-tongue as the
medium of teaching.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the avian flu, Tung said that the government
attaches great importance to public health. He expressed his
thanks to various sectors that have provided help for the massive
killing of chickens in Hong Kong to prevent possible spread of
bird flu.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the mother tongue teaching, Tung said that the
purpose is to let students to grasp both Chinese and English
languages and the three spoken languages in Hong Kong --
Cantonese, English and Putonghua (Mandarin Chinese).
</P>
<P>
Tung said that education experts pointed out that in the
environment of mother tongue teaching, students can learn their
subjects better.
</P>
<P>
Tung also said that the government will offer more financial
aid to schools that conduct mother tongue teaching.
</P>
<P>
Upon the closing of the session, Rita Fan, president of the PLC
said that the PLC supports Tung in his determination to fight for
the best of Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
