<HEADLINE> US-Israeli Talks Focus on Peace Process, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton will
limit his discussion with Israel Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
next week to merely the Middle East peace process, a U.S. official
said today.
</P>
<P>
"This is not designed to be a stop-by visit by the prime
minister to go over broad regional issues," the official said.
"This is focused on what Israel needs to do and what the
Palestinian Authority needs to do to get the peace process back on
track."
</P>
<P>
The official said the meeting Tuesday was scheduled for one
hour and the two leaders would not share a meal.
</P>
<P>
Irael's media have reported that the Clinton administration had
turned a request from Netanyahu to cover other issues in the
meeting and they interpreted the absence of a meal as a sign of
U.S. impatience with Israel over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But the official said the planned agenda for the meeting and
the absence of the meal were arranged because of Clinton's tight
schedule. There is not an effort to set a frosty tone for the
visit.
</P>
<P>
He said apart from the talks with the president, Netanyahu will
have separate meetings with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger Tuesday where broad
issues are expected to come up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
