<HEADLINE> Russia Proposes Sending Spy Planes for UN to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev proposed here today that Russia can send its spy planes
for the United Nations to Iraq to ensure the control of
disarmament there by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Sergeyev, who was on a visit
in the French capital, as saying that if Iraq is opposed to the
use of U2 spy plane of the United States by the U.N. in
supervising the disarmament, Russia "is ready to propose its own
planes."
</P>
<P>
He said that Russian planes own the same functions as the U.S.
planes.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev also emphasized the Russia is opposed to the use of
force against Iraq, and recalled that both Russia nad France
"contributed a lot to" a diplomatic solution to the last
confrontation between Iraq and the U.N arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The Russian defense minister held talks with his French
counterpart, Alain Richard, today.
</P>
<P>
A new crisis has erupted between Iraq and the United Nations
arms inspectors in Iraq after the Iraqi government blocked an
inspectors' team headed by a U.S. Gulf War veteran from pursuing
its work.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council called the Iraqi decision
"unacceptable" Wednesday. 
</P>
