<HEADLINE> Kenya Committed to Improving Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Newly-elected President Daniel
arap Moi today said that his government is committed to improving
investment environment to attract more investment.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the 1998 Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE)
market this morning, Moi said his presence at NSE underscored
that "my government places economic growth high on its agenda."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government would focus more attention to the
task of alleviating poverty and improving people's living
standards through speedy economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Moi pointed out that the newly appointed cabinet would make
efforts to ensure stable macro-economic environment which is a
pre-requisite for attracting investments.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Kenya's inflation has been tamed to single
digit while the exchange rate has been fairly smooth and
predictable.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader stated that the infrastructure of the east
African country, especially the road network, had been
deteriorated during the past three months due to the continuous
heavy rains caused by the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government will give special attention in
maintaining the dilapidated road network to acceptable standards
as a sound infrastructural network is key to the socio-economic
development, he added.
</P>
<P>
President Moi expressed his government's determination to
stamp out corruption which, he said, is "a cancer that has
contributed to the inefficient management of public resources and
tarnished the name of our country both locally and
internationally."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the head of state noted that Kenya is committed to
the integration of the great east African market as a way of
accelerating economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi Stock Exchange was started in 1954 and since then
the NSE has made great contributions to Kenya's economic
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
