<HEADLINE> Three South Asian Nation Summit Vows Close Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The one-day
Bangladesh-India-Pakistan business summit ended here on Thursday
after adopting a joint declaration calling for greater
consultations and close economic cooperation among the three South
Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the summit as "constructive and useful", the
declaration said the three countries possess vast human and
natural resources, offering great opportunities for economic and
social development.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the South Asian region is an attractive
destination for foreign direct investment, with a considerable
scope for promoting investment through mutual cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The heads of government stressed the importance to develop
infrastructure and adequate communications network to accelerate
economic cooperation, acknowledging that inadequate communication
facilities constitute a major obstacle to closer economic
cooperation, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
They are committed to the establishment of a free trade area in
South Asia by the year 2001, it added.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in science and technology is imperative in ensuring
global competitiveness and acceleration of development in the
region, the declaration pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral arrived here on
Wednesday afternoon and left for home Thursday night, and
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who arrived Thursday
morning, will stay here for a two-day official visit to
Bangladesh.  
</P>
