<HEADLINE> Canada's Airlines Vie for Asian Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The fight between Canada's two
major airlines for Asian routes will likely intensify once Air
Canada buys new wide-body jets, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Lamar Durrett, president and chief executive of Air Canada,
said he expects the company's board to approve the acquisition of
five new jets when it meets in March.
</P>
<P>
The new jets will be capable of flying Toronto to Hong Kong
non-stop, according to the Financial Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In this case, Air Canada will likely step up its lobbying of
the federal government for permission to fly more often to Asia.
</P>
<P>
At present, Air Canada is only allowed to fly four times a week
from Vancouver to Hong Kong, but wants to do so daily and add
flights from Toronto, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Its arch rival Canadian Airlines International Ltd., whose
survival hinges on its dominance of the Canada-Asia market, has
said it would resist any changes to air routes. 
</P>
