<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF Welcome Indonesian Reform Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) today expressed
their welcome and pleasure for Indonesia's extensive new
commitment to economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
"This is a huge step forward in restoring investor confidence,"
World Bank President James D. Wolfensohn said. "The program
contains just about everything the government can hope to do to
get its economy back on track and to protect the poor from the
worst effects of the financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank was ready to do its share in providing
quick-disbursing loans in support of the reforms and in helping
the Indonesian government to carry out the program, Wolfensohn
stated.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank approved in December last year a 20 million U.S.
dollar Banking Reform Assistance Project as technical assistance
to help the Indonesian government implement banking sector
reforms. This loan will be followed by a financial sector
adjustment loan, a structural adjustment loan, a rural employment
project and an urban community works project. The planned loans
will reach 3 billion dollars and will be supplemented by the World
Bank's normal investment operations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus issued a
statement expressing his pleasure over the preliminary agreement
with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence in the success of the program which
includes the budget cut, fiscal transparency, monetary policy,
bank and corporate sector restructuring and structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
"The program provides for strengthened measures targeted to
alleviating the plight of the most vulnerable people in the
country," Camdessus noted.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief has paid a visit to Indonesia to push for
stronger and quicker reforms amid concern that President Suharto
was reluctant to implement austerity measures linked to a 40
billion dollar rescue package.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus revealed that World Bank President Wolfensohn will
also visit Indonesia very soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers is
on a whirlwind Asia tour aimed at restoring confidence in the
region's battered currencies and markets.
</P>
<P>
Since July, the Washington-based IMF has arranged more than 100
billion dollars in bailouts for South Korea, Indonesia and
Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
