<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Schools Hit by Headteacher Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Record numbers of state schools
in Britain advertised for headteachers in 1997, said local press
reports today.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures from a survey by the National Association of
Head Teachers, reports said that a record one in 10 state schools
which amount to a total number of 2,411 schools could not find
competent heads and deputies.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that the situation was partly because of senior
staff seeking early retirement before changes in pension
regulations.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 389 secondary schools advertised for heads
last year, compared with 258 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The situation was much worse in primary schools where vacancies
for headteachers passed the 2,000 mark to reach 2,022 for the
first time since the 1980s despite the fact that 600 headteacher
posts were cut between 1991 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, among all the schools advertised for headteachers,
14 percent of secondary schools and 24 percent of primary schools
failed to attract candidates of sufficient caliber during the
first round of interviews and were forced to readvertise the
posts.
</P>
<P>
The worst area was inner London, where more than 50 percent of
posts had to be readvertised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
