<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Offers Loans to Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
made available a 35 million U.S. Dollars loan facility to new and
existing small- to medium-scale exporters aimed at ensuring
increased and sustainable export-led growth by the sector.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Industry and Commerce said in a statement
today the loan would be disbursed by the apex unit of the Reserve
Bank of Zimbabwe through most local banks and financial
institutions which are participating in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
Eligible borrowers include individuals and companies employing
not more than one hundred people and have net assets, excluding
land, not exceeding 500,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said all exports qualify except tobacco and that
borrowers can apply for up to 150,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
On contribution by the borrower, the ministry said, "borrowers
are expected to contribute at least 20 percent toward the total
costs of executing the export order either in cash or in kind."
</P>
<P>
Lending rates would be determined by the financial
institutions and would be commensurate with costs and risks of
each application.
</P>
<P>
"Successful applicants are required to have either an
irrevocable letter of credit or a confirmed export order
supported by export credit insurance," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It added, "to enhance the security offered by the borrower to
the participating financial institution, the credit guarantee
agency within the apex unit can cover default risk up to 80
percent of the loan amount." 
</P>
</TEXT>
