<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia, Botswana to Hold Summit over Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma and his Botswana counterpart Ketumile Masire will meet to
discuss rising tensions over a small island in the Linyanti River
bordering the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In its statement issued today, the Namibian Foreign Ministry
urged Namibians, and in particular those from Singobeka village
near Situngu Island in the Caprivi Region, to "remain calm and
refrained from taking unwise steps".
</P>
<P>
"The president is dealing personally with the Situngu Island
issue," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"It is Namibia's strong belief that Namibia-Botswana relations
are too critical for both sides to suffer under a heavy load of
boundary claims and military operations," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Botswana soldiers had occupied Situngu
Island and had harassed Namibian farmers who had crops planted
there.
</P>
<P>
However, the Botswana High Commission in Windhoek denied the
reports, saying at no time did Botswana troops cross the Linyanti
River into Namibians territory.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact, in order to plough fields on the
Botswana side of th border, the Namibian nationals actually cross
the Linyanti River using canoes in the deeper areas, and where
the river is low they place logs on the papyrus to cross into
Botswana," the commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The island dispute is being addressed by the Namibian-Botswana
joint commission on defense and security, which met a number of
times last year.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to the inflammatory press reports, the operatives of
the two countries pose no danger to each other or the security of
the two countries," the Botswana statement said.
</P>
<P>
The world court in the Hague is to adjudicate on another
disputed small island in the Chobe River bordering Namibia and
Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
