<HEADLINE> S. Africa Enforces First Provincial Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's first
provincial constitution was signed into law today by Western Cape
Premier Hernus Kriel, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
About 200 African National Congress (ANC) and South African
Communist Party supporters sang and chanted in a peaceful protest
outside the provincial legislature building while the signing
ceremony was under way, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Western Cape is the only province governed by the opposition
National Party (NP).
</P>
<P>
The constitution, certified by the Constitutional Court late
last year as complying with the national constitution, provides
for Kriel to constitute his own cabinet, breaking up the former
government of provincial unity stipulated by the 1993 national
interim constitution.
</P>
<P>
The ANC had four out of 10 cabinet ministers (members of
executive committee, or MECs), while it has chosen to be excluded
from the new 12-member provincial cabinet to be sworn in next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ANC declined to take up two posts offered to it by Kriel,
arguing that as the second biggest party in the province in terms
of the 1994 general election, it should have remained entitled to
at least the four MECs it had previously had.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party (DP) and African Christian Democratic
Party have one post each in the new cabinet, with the NP
occupying the other positions.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet would consist of eight whites and four
coloreds without any African.
</P>
<P>
Kriel has said the signing of the constitution heralded a new
era in the country's constitutional process.
</P>
<P>
"We are making use of a constitutional right which can promote
the eventual coming into being of a fully-fledged federal
dispensation."
</P>
<P>
The ANC, in calling on the people of the Western Cape to join
it in protesting against the constitution, said, "we need to send
a clear message to the National Party that their constitution
does not enjoy any legitimacy."
</P>
<P>
It was clear that the NP had chosen a path of division and
conflict by ending the government of unity in the province and
kicking out the four ANC MECs, the ANC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The ANC accused Kriel and his NP of being "nothing less than
racism", referring to the fact that Africans were excluded from
the new provincial cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The NP had chosen a path against transformation and the
country's nation-building project, the ANC said. "They have
chosen to divide and rule."
</P>
<P>
DP Western Cape leader Hennie Bester, who chaired the
provincial committee that drew up the constitution, welcomed its
signing and coming into operation.
</P>
<P>
"It heralds the birth of a new and exciting era for this part
of our country," said Bester, who is to become the new economic
affairs MEC in Western Cape.
</P>
<P>
He accused the ANC of hypocrisy, saying that the ANC had never
been in favor of a continuation of the government of provincial
unity during the constitution-writing process.
</P>
<P>
"They only wanted to keep their jobs until 1999," SAPA quoted
Bester as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Blasts Israel for Shrinking From Commitments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERICHO, PALESTINE, January 15 (Xinhua) -- In response to an
Israeli Cabinet decision to retain vast areas of the West Bank, a
leading Palestinian negotiator Thursday blasted Israel for
refusing to implement signed agreements by using any excuses.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, Minister of Local Governments in the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA), made the accusation at a news
conference held here. This was the first official response to an
Israel document that listed a number of obligations it requires
the PNA to fulfill before any Israeli troop redeployment in the
West Bank can be carried out.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh formally
informed the PNA of the Israeli Cabinet document in a letter sent
to him Wednesday. The document demanded the PNA fight terrorism,
restrict police forces and activities in Jerusalem, and extradite
terror suspects.
</P>
<P>
He blasted Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for
attempting to use any excuses to avoid implementation of signed
agreements. "The aim of the game of Mr. Netanyahu is very
clear: it will use any excuse and pretext for Mr. Netanyahu not to
implement the further redeployment," he said.
</P>
<P>
As to the Israeli demand for tougher measures against
terrorism, Erekat reminded Netanyahu that it was the Israeli side
that refused to attend a ceremony scheduled on December 22, 1997,
to conclude and sign a memorandum of understanding on security
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the memorandum, mediated by the United States,
contains the PNA promise to "zero tolerance" of violence against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of revising the Palestinian Charter, Erekat noted
that it has already been modified in April, 1996 by the
Palestinian National Council to eliminate the articles calling for
Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
Israel maintains that the charter has not been in fact revised
since no new version has been drafted. Erekat firmly rejected the
Israeli notion, saying "it's our Palestinians' business whether we
have a new charter or not."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Jerusalem, Erekat said the status of Jerusalem
is open to final-status talks and that doest not mean Jerusalem
belongs to Israel before the talks begin. He said the previous
Labor government in Israel pledged to preserve all existing PNA
institutions in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Erekat also attacked Israeli Cabinet's recent debate on setting
up security zones in the West Bank as a "unilateral declaration that
there will be no peace process."
</P>
<P>
Israeli ministers have been holding consecutive sessions over
the past few days in a bid to work out maps which will lead to
Israel's continued control over at least half of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"This is the most dangerous development till this moment by
Mr. Netanyahu," said Erekat, warning that the Palestinians are
running out of their patience toward the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
The senior negotiator called on responsible international
leaders to intervene in the deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace
negotiations so as to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the best way to advance the peace process is for Israel
to honor the United Nations Security Council Resolution 242 and
the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Erekat also disclosed that PNA President Yasser Arafat would
present U.S. President Bill Clinton a comprehensive road-map on
reviving the peace process, including demands on Israel's
fulfillment of its commitments and proposals on Israeli
redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is to hold separate talks with Netanyahu and Arafat in
Washington next week in an effort to restart the peace
process, stalled since Israel went ahead with Jewish settlement
expansion in East Jerusalem in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
