<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans' Rally Supports Iraqi Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 15 (Xinhua) -- A group of U.S. citizens held a
demonstration Thursday before U.N. office in Baghdad to show
support for the Iraqis in their struggle to have the economic
sanctions lifted, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
A demonstrator John Hide told the INA that they would observe a
hunger strike in the coming three days before the United Nations
Special Commission, which is responsible for verifying the
elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction ordered by the
U.N. in 1991 after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators belong to a U.S. organization called "Voices
in the Wildness," which upholds the slogan of lifting the
sanctions against the Iraqi people, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
Hide said the hunger strikers intended to express their sorrow
for the hardship suffered by the Iraqis due to U.N. sanctions
which have been mounted by direct U.S. support.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed economic sanctions on Iraq after its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990, which bars Iraq from exporting oil, its main
revenue earner.
</P>
<P>
Jane Hoscank, a woman demonstrator, said they were demanding
for an end to the crippling economic sanctions on Iraq and U.S.
military threats to the Iraqi people, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
She called on world humanitarian organizations to join hands in
exposing the scandalous embargo policy and its grave consequences
on Iraqi children and elderly.
</P>
<P>
Another member Eline Barfield criticized the U.S. for
masterminding most of the U.N. Security Council resolutions on
Iraq, which she said were arbitrary and inhuman.
</P>
<P>
She said the oil-for-food agreement between the U.N. and Iraq
proved to be ineffective in meeting the growing needs of the Iraqi
people for food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that true relief of the Iraqi people's sufferings
is the lifting of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal between Iraq and the U.N. allows Iraq to
sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil in every six months to
buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The "Voices in the Wildness" organization has dispatched nine
teams to Iraq, which have brought large amount of medicine and
toys to the Iraqi children hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
