<HEADLINE> Iraq Starts Exporting Oil Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 15 (Xinhua)-- Iraq has started exporting the
first batch of its oil under the third phase of the
Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program through its southern port of
Al-Bark, Iraq's official news agency INA reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted Director General of South Oil Company Yassin
Ad-Dabbouri as saying that the first oil tanker, Inenbra, has been
loaded with 600,000 barrels of Iraqi crude oil.
</P>
<P>
The second super tanker, Nacazaki, is due to arrive on Friday
to be loaded with 290,000 barrels of Iraqi crude oil, said Yassin.
</P>
<P>
The quantities of Iraqi Oil exported under the first phase
totaled 51 million barrels and was carried by 44 oil tankers,
while in the second phase, it reached 54 million barrels and was
carried by 30 tankers, Yassin added.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal, first implemented in December
1996, was renewed last month for the third time, but Iraq refused
to export oil until U.N. chief Kofi Annan approved its food
distribution plan earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Iraq is allowed to export 2 billion U.S.
dollars worth of oil every six months to buy food, medicine and
other humanitarian supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
