<HEADLINE> Angolan President to Meet UNITA Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos and the former rebel UNITA (the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola) Jonas Savimbi are to meet by the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Riberto de Almneida, speaker of the Angolan Parliament who is
on his Italian tour, said in Rome today that the meeting, the
fifth since the Lusaka Peace Protocol in 1994, would be held in
Luanda.
</P>
<P>
He said both sides are paying much attention to the meeting
and the special committees on both sides are discussing on the
details concerning the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a UNITA high-level delegation is to
arrive at Luanda to consult with the government on issues
concerning the summit meeting, including the number of guards
Savimbi should take for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Both sides believed peace process have developed into a
certain level which makes it necessary for such a meeting,
Almneida said.
</P>
<P>
The summit, if held, would serve as an important landmark in
Angolan peace process, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the new year, both the government and UNITA
have expressed that they are hoping to accomplish the peace
process by the end of February, and UNITA has handed over about
31 diamond mines it used to control to the government, thus
ending one of the most sticky problems in the peace process in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
