<HEADLINE> US Experts Reconsider Asia Crisis Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Top American economists are
growing more pessimistic about the impact of the Asian financial
turmoil on the U.S. economy, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis has been unfolding faster and more seriously than
people have anticipated," says Robert McGee, economist at Tokai
Bank in New York.
</P>
<P>
Many U.S. economists have been citing the Asia crisis as the
biggest threat the country's economy is facing. They estimate that
it will reduce growth some 0.6 percentage points this year and
balloon the trade deficit by nearly 40 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The USA TODAY quarterly economic survey of 55 economists
forecast that economic growth will slow sharply to 2.4 percent in
1998 from 3.5 percent or more last year as the Asia crisis hurts
U.S. exports and takes a bite out of corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
But the reports said that most of the economists still did not
expect the fallout to derail the nearly seven-year expansion of
the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
They also predict that U.S. unemployment will remain under 5
percent through 1998, keeping the jobless rate at its lowest
levels since the early 1970s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
