<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Chemical Output Slips as Drug Sector Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The UK chemical industry output
last year slipped for the first time since 1990 because of
weakness in the pharmaceutical sector and export pressures, a
conference was told here today.
</P>
<P>
Total production dropped 0.2 percent on the back of a 1.5
percent fall in the contribution from pharmaceuticals, which
accounts for more than a quarter of the industry output, Malcolm
Mitchell, BP Chemicals economist, said at the conference.
</P>
<P>
The growth in export volume more than halved from 6.7 percent
in 1996 to 3 percent but the strength of sterling meant foreign
trade in value terms was down 3 percent - 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prospects for the UK industry this year remain "more difficult"
compared with the rest of Europe, said a delegate at the
conference organized by the Chemical Industries Association.
</P>
<P>
UK chemicals growth, predicted to be 2 percent, will be the
most sluggish among the big four, though export growth is forecast
to edge up to 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
German output is projected to grow by 4 percent against 6
percent last year, with France 3.1 percent (4.6 percent last year)
and Italy 2.7 percent (2.5 percent last year). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
