<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-15 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreements More Important Than Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat said in Hebron Thursday
that for the peace process, signed agreements are more important
than the government decisions.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after his meeting with visiting British
Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs Derek Fatchett and EU peace
envoy Miguel Moratinos, Arafat said the Israeli government is
putting more road blocks for the Washington summit meetings to be
held later this month.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu are
sheduled to hold talks separately next weeek in Washington
with U.S. President Bill Clinton on reviving the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Although Israel is trying to place more obstacles in the
peace process, the PNA will definitly continue to push this
process forward, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Arafat to criticize the
Israeli government after it decided on Wednesday to put about
60 percent of the PNA's West bank territories under its
control.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet decided on Wednesday not to hand over to the
PNA such areas of vital security interests including two security
strips on each side of the West Bank, water resources, certain
roads, areas surrounding Jerusalem, Jewish settlements and Jewish
historical sites in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
This decision of the Israeli cabinet has faced sharp crticisim
from the PNA and the international community.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, who arrived here on Wednesday for a three-day visit
to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule area, told reporters after
his meeting with Arafat that Britain is against the Israel's
settlement policy and its unilateral actions.
</P>
<P>
The United States was also not happy after learning it.
</P>
<P>
"We are taken by surprise and it is not helpful to our ability
to conduct diplomacy on this important subject in advance of the
(Washington) meetings," State Department Spokesman James Foley
was reportedly said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The America's reaction also caused Netanyahu off-guard
again. Netanyahu this morning told his cabinet, which met for the
fourth time this week to discuss the scope of the second stage
troop redeployment in the West Bank, that the size of the second
stage redeployment will depend on whether there will be a third
stage redeployment, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet once again has not reached a final decision on
this issue, and decided to meet again on Sunday for further
discussion.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, who did not turn up at
today's cabinet meeting, told the high-ranking military officers
in Tel Aviv that if there is no redeployment, there will
bo no problem for him to resign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
