<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Rate Ends Year Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year
inflation ended the year at 20.1 percent, up 0.7 percentage
points, underpinned by a hike in all components, the Central
Statistical Office said today.
</P>
<P>
Annual rate of inflation on one hand was pegged at 18.6
percent last year, about 3 percentage points lower than 1996, the
drastic fall to 14.4 percent in September having contributed to
this.
</P>
<P>
Inflation had been on a continuous upward trend since October
and market analysts foresaw this continuing into the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
They had predicted inflation would end the year at around 19
percent, but due to a spate of administered price increases and
above inflation wage settlements, the rate shot up.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Bank also predicted a higher annual rate of
inflation this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
