<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airbus Weighing Super Passenger Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The German partner of the Airbus
Industrie today said the European planemaker is working seriously
to examine the feasibility of building a 600-seater super
passenger jet in a bid to boost its share in the global market.
</P>
<P>
Gustav Humbert, a senior manager with the German Daimler-Benz
Aerospace Airbus GmbH, said that he expected the technical and
finanicial problems concerning the super jumbo project to be
clarified by the end of this year or the beginning of next year so
that a final decision on whether to proceed with the project could
be made in 1999.
</P>
<P>
At issue is a 600-passenger double-decker plane, dubbed the
A3XX, which could have a range of 13,440 to 15,360 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Airbus promises that the super jumbo will be faster, quieter,
more cost-efficient and able to fly farther than the Boeing 747
which was introduced by the U.S. Boeing Co. nearly 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Critics, however, say that the new jet, which will cost a
minimum of 10 billion U.S. dollars to produce, will have a
formidable price tag. And most fundamentally, they are also not
sure whether the world will really need a passenger jet larger
than the 420-seat Boeing 747.
</P>
<P>
Although both Airbus and Boeing agree that passenger traffic
will nearly triple in 20 years, Boeing believes that smaller,
longer-range planes will meet the needs of most future travelers,
industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
According to Humbert, if executives give the project the green
light, the first A3XX could be delivered as early as 2003. He also
expressed the belief that with the introduction of the new jet,
Airbus should be able to boost its global market share to 50
percent from about 40 percent today.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Eberhard Birke, a director of the German Aviation
and Aerospace Industry Federation, said today in Bonn that Airbus
had received 29.6 billion U.S. dollars in binding orders for 460
planes in 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the current year, Airbus would deliver 235 planes, and from
1999 to 2001, it was planning to have an annual production of
about 260 planes, Birke said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
