<HEADLINE> Britain Criticizes US Iran Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The British foreign
secretary today criticized the U.S. policy toward Iran, saying
isolation of the Islamic country would not work.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the European Institute in Washington, Robin Cook
said, "We must respond to the dangers posed by isolating as well
as the opportunities. But isolating Iran is not the right
response."
</P>
<P>
Cook, current president of the European Union, condemned the
Iran-Libya Sanctions Act punishing foreign companies investing in
Iran's oil and gas sectors, saying it was unacceptable to European
states and counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
He said that by punishing foreign companies under the Sanctions
Act, the United States risked provoking a transatlantic trade war,
which he said could "benefit only the hawks in Iran."
</P>
<P>
Britain is making the coordination of transatlantic policy on
Iran a priority of its tenure of the six-month EU presidency,
which took over on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Britain and its European allies could not forge a new
partnership with the United States on Iran "while we are looking
down the barrel of the Sanctions Act gun," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook welcomed Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's appeal for
cultural exchanges between the United States and Iran, saying,
"There are the first signs of Glasnost appearing in Iran and we
must do what we can to encourage it."
</P>
<P>
Cook also reiterated Britain's strong support for Washington's
tough position against Iraq to force it to allow U.N. weapons
inspectors access to any sites they want for checking weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed the U.N. Security Council must stand by its
commitment that sanctions were being applied "for specific
purposes." "There is light at the end of the tunnel for Iraq," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Once Saddam Hussein complies fully with the Security Council's
requirements on weapons of mass destruction, then the U.N. will
need to take action on the oil embargo (on Iraq)," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
