<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Likely to Concede to S. Leone Junta: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations might prepare
to make some concessions to the ruling military junta of Sierra
Leone to break the deadlock in the peace process in the troubled
west African country.
</P>
<P>
The "strongest" indication was given by UN special envoy
Francis Okello in Freetown today, according to a British
Broadcasting Corportion report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in Sierra Leone has been stalled since the
junta, which seized power in a coup last May, said the peace plan
to hand over power to ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah by
April 22 this year had become unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
Koroma insisted that the former rebel leader should be
released from alleged detention in Nigeria, his army not be
disarmed and the dominant role of Nigeria in the west African
peacekeeping force be diminished.
</P>
<P>
These are the sticking points of Koroma during the past two
days' meetings with the UN fact-finding team led by Okello, which
arrived in the capital Freetown only on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to what he described as a "comprehensive and very
useful statement" by Koroma shortly after the team's arrival,
Okello said that the three fundamental issues raised by the junta
since the signing of the Conakry peace accord last October are
"legitimate".
</P>
<P>
The envoy promised the junta that he had taken "very careful"
notes of their concern and suggestions and would report carefully
and objectively to the UN secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
"I think that one of our recommendations will be that there
shall be a meeting between the two sides as soon as possible to
review these concerns," Okello said.
</P>
<P>
The report also quoted Koroma as saying that these issues were
raised in Conakry, Guinea last October, but time was not in favor
of his delegation.
</P>
<P>
The junta leader said that not signing the peace accord at
that time would have sent a wrong signal to the world.
</P>
<P>
However, Koroma said the junta was reminded today that the
overall commitment of the Conakry peace plan was that there shall
be a restitution of constitutional order and the reestablishment
of the constitutionally elected Sierra Leonean government in
April 1988.
</P>
<P>
So far no response has been heard from the Economic Community
of West African States, which has been asking the junta to stick
to the Conakry accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
