<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Strives to Ease Power Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is striving to
solve the electricity shortage problem through developing a
number of power projects, Energy and Minerals Minister Abdallah
Kigoda said here today.
</P>
<P>
The power rationing system, which has been carried out since
1992, will become a history when the projects are completed, the
minister said while addressing the Tanzania Electric Supply
Company Limited (TANESCO) workers at the firm's headquarters
office.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kihansi Power project will generate 60 megawatts
of electricity, and the Songosongo gas project will produce 37
megawatts of electricity by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Other projects include the Malaysian IPTL project which is
expected to generate 100 megawatts. British company Agrreko's
power project will be able to generate another 100 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
Electricity generated from the power barge in the sea is
expected to reach between 100 and 130 megawatts, and the
government is still seeking funds to construct the Rumakali and
Ruhuji power projects which are expected to produce a total of
600 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The projects will reduce the country's heavy dependence on
hydro-electricity to a great extent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Following a severe drought, Tanzania introduced power
rationing system in early September last year. People in a number
of areas complained that they had no supply of electricity in
five days a week during the worst period.
</P>
<P>
The power supply situation did not come back to normal until
early this month thanks to El Nino rains pouring into major dams
of the country from December.
</P>
<P>
"We have realized our problems so we should strive to make
sure that the power rationing system does not come again," Kigoda
said.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, the country's industries will have an even higher
demand for power, and the present generating capacity of 360
megawatts is far from enough, he noted.
</P>
<P>
To improve working efficiency, the minister said TANESCO, the
country's major power supplier, will be restructured and some
workers will be retrenched to enhance the company's efficiency.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the official revealed that the country will
take measures to encourage private investment in the power
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN/ECE: 1997 World Crude Steel Production Reaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- World crude steel production is
estimated to reach a record level of 798.5 million tons in 1997,
6.6 percent higher than the previous year, according to a press
release by the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe
(UN/ECE).
</P>
<P>
The old record of 784.9 million tons was set in 1989, said the
UN/ECE in its first estimates on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in 1997 is largely due to a rebound in economic
growth in the European Union and to a continuous increase in new
crude steel-making capacity in the United States of America and in
Asia, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
China was the world'largest steel producer for the second
consecutive year. It was followed by Japan, the US, the Russian
Federation, Germany and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Asia saw dynamic growth in steel production in 1997. China
showed a steady rising trend of crude steel production despite
official prohibition of the construction of large capacity
greenfield steelworks. Production increased from 100.00 million
tons in 1996 to 107.3 million tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, output increased by 6.0 percent and exceeded the 100
million ton level for the first time in two years (104.7 million
tons) owing to steel exports supported by the devaluation of the
Yen.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, production rose by 8.4 percent (42.18 million
tons) and in Taiwan Province of China by 31.2 percent (15.87
million tons).
</P>
<P>
Total crude steel production within the EU increased by 9.1
percent to 159.9 million tons. In the US, production reached its
highest level since 1981, increasing from 94.7 million tons in
1996 to 99.2 million tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In central europe as a whole, crude steel production recovered
from a decline registered in 1996, reflected by a surge in steel
exports, the UN/ECE said.
</P>
<P>
However, in the Russian Federation, crude steel production
declined by 2.1 percent owing to a fall in domestic steel
consumption, although an increase in steel exports made up for
this shortfall to some degree.
</P>
<P>
In Latin America, crude steel production registered an increase
of 4.5 percent as a whole, with a 6.6 percent increase in Mexico
and 3.8 percent in Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
