<HEADLINE> Lithuania Seeking for Good Relations with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Lithuania hopes that Russia will
not reproach the Baltic states with the signing of the U.S.-
Baltic Partnership Charter to be held in Washington on January 16,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported from Vilnius, Lithuania, on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the ELTA news agency Lithuanian Prime
Minister Gediminas Vagnorius said, "the most important document
stresses the need to develop good relations with Moscow."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Charter should not infringe upon the
development of good relations between Lithuania and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania is the first country among the former Soviet
republics which signed the border treaty with Russia, and it is
extremely interested in continuing this process, Vagnorius said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the U.S.- Baltic Charter is not aimed against
Russia. On the contrary, it stresses the need to establish
fruitful and good neighbourly relations between the Baltic states
and Moscow, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today the Russian side expressed "deep concern" over
the signing of a U.S.- Baltic Partnership Charter. The Russian
Duma and Foreign Ministry hold that it indicates the beginning of
preparations for the next stage of NATO's eastward expansion since
the Baltic states have refused to accept the security guarantees
proposed by the Russian president.
</P>
<P>
The Lithuanian prime minister believed that tension would not
grow between Russia and the Baltic countries if Vilnius and
Washington sign a political declaration on Lithuania's security.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of the three Baltic states are now visiting
Washington for the signing with the U.S. President Bill Clinton
the Partnership Charter. 
</P>
