<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Thursday that he was encouraged by a U.N. Security Council
statement demanding Iraq to stop blocking an American-led weapons
inspection team from doing its job.
</P>
<P>
He said it was because even those who had been more sympathetic
to Iraq "saw through" Iraq's complaints of unbalanced composition
of the weapons inspection team and allegation of spying by former
marine Scott Ritter, who led the inspection team.
</P>
<P>
"I am very encouraged that even those who had been more
sympathetic to Iraq saw through this totally unacceptable action,"
Clinton told reporters on the South Lawn at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council on Wednesday unanimously adopted the
statement deploring the blocking of the Ritter-led inspection team
and "Iraiq's failure to fulfill its obligations to provide the
inspectors with full, unconditional and immediate access to all
sites."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States would wait and see what would
happen following the Security Council statement and after U.N.
weapons inspection chief Richard Butler's trip to Baghdad to
resolve the latest standoff between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
