<HEADLINE> Russian Vice-Premiers' Duties Re-Assigned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin signed a document Friday to re-allocate the duties of
the Vice-Premiers in an effort to ensure the reforms of the main
branches of the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted Chernomyrdin as saying that
the First Vice-Premier Anatoly Chubais "will be in charge of the
entire economy, supervising the actions of all agencies to realize
the medium-term development program of the Russian Federation."
</P>
<P>
Chubais will look after the Finance Ministry's activities in
working out financial development programs, in particular the
budget and the collection of budget revenue.
</P>
<P>
First Vice-Premier Boris Nemtsov, Chernomyrdin said, will
supervise reform-related matters, including the
housing-and-utilities reform, the activities of the Transport
Commission, the energy and natural monopolies services.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Anatoly Kulikov has retained charge of
the Interior Ministry only. He will supervise the Federal Railroad
Troops Service and the collection of the budget revenue by the
State Customs Committee, the Federal Taxation Police Service and
the Federal Currency and Export Control Service.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin described the move as "nothing sensational,"
saying that the distribution of the vice-premiers' duties "have
always been subject to change or re-distribution depending on the
government's task at each specific stage." 
</P>
</TEXT>
