<HEADLINE> Somali Factions Welcome Ali Mahdi's Return From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The armed militia forces of
Mogadishu's main factions today for the first time in six years
came out together at Isaley airstrip to welcome a delegation led
by Mr Ali Mahdi Mohamed, who has signed a peace pact in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Painted battle wagons from Hussein Aidid's faction and
technical wagons from Osman Ali Atto together with those of Ali
Mahdi accompanied by hundreds of militiamen from all sides have
lined up the road between Mogadishu and Isaley airstrip, 15 km
North of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Mogadishu's people mainly from North Mogadishu
were transported with buses and lorries to the airstrip for the
arrival of Ali Mahdi's delegation which has been abroad for more
than four months.
</P>
<P>
People carrying a portrait of Ali Mahdi, and placards and
waving green leaves sang the national anthem of the divided
nation which has been plunged into clan wars since the overthrow
of former Somali President S. Barre in 1991.
</P>
<P>
At the heavily guarded airstrip, just beside the plane, the
top political aids of the three main factions gave a hug and hand
shake to Ali Mahdi Mohamed and other members of his delegation,
the first of the Cairo signatories to reach the capital.
</P>
<P>
Most of the cheering crowds were expected to see a return of
the factional leaders together. However, their hope has dashed
following a minor misunderstanding between the joint technical
committee.
</P>
<P>
During the speeches at Ali Mahdi's residence, Issa Weheliye
Malin, a member of the welcoming committee told the people that
Mogadishu will be a peaceful place if an equal effort is exerted
on pacifying the capital just as the factional leaders do at the
welcome ceremony today.
</P>
<P>
"This is the beginning of a new hope for Mogadishu and Somalia
as a whole," said Mr Malin.
</P>
<P>
Among the people that welcomed and hugged Ali Mahdi's
delegation today is his main arch rival in North Mogadishu,
religious leader Sheikh Ali Sheikh Mohamud (Sheikh Ali Dhere).
The conflicts between them led to the collapse of the Islamic
courts in North Mogadishu. And the two men embraced each other at
the airport to show to the public a sign of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
The North Mogadishu faction leader, Ali Mahdi Mohamed, has
urged the Somalis to take and implement the historic Cairo
agreement reached by his National Salvation Council Alliance and
Hussein Aidid last year.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the people of Mogadishu to orchestrate a
similar warm welcome later for Hussein Aidid and other factions.
</P>
<P>
Aidid and Osman Atto who are currently in Cairo are expected
to arrive together at km-50 road Sunday according to the
preparatory committee for a mild reception of the leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
