<HEADLINE> Seminar Discusses How China's Rural Firms Can Clean Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and foreign
environmental experts gathered in the city of Xiamen in the
southeastern Chinese province of Fujian yesterday to discuss ways
to help the country's rural firms clean up their production
methods.
</P>
<P>
Experts agree that the question of whether China can reach its
environmental protection goals by the year 2000 depends largely on
the extent to which it can control pollution caused by the growing
number of township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by the National Environmental Protection Agency
and the Ministry of Agriculture found that township enterprises,
which are often small in scale but big in energy consumption, are
responsible for half the industrial pollution in China.
</P>
<P>
Experts suggest that cleaner production methods be used to cut
pollution to a minimum. At the seminar they discussed
concrete ways to standardize practice, set up administrative
agencies, designate piloting firms, and train personnel.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was sponsored by the China Environment and
Development International Cooperation Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Rejects Talks With US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei Friday rejected any talks and ties with
the United States, saying they would be harmful to the Iranian
nation and the Islamic system.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the prayer congregation on the campus of Tehran
University in the morning, Khamenei said that as before Iran would
stand firmly on its stances and would never abandon its values and
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
"The Iranian nation stands against the United States, regards
it as 'Great Satan,' and even dislikes to speak to it," Tehran
radio quoted the Iranian leader as saying.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Khamenei's strong-worded remark was
unexpected, particularly for the United States. This came after
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami called for cultural dialog
between Iranian and American nations although he said there was
"no need to have ties with the U.S.."
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that any talks and ties with the U.S. would
damage the Islamic Revolution led by the Iranian late supreme
leader Imam Khomeini and would make the country lose its
independence "which was achieved by the Iranian nation through
struggle against the world powers for over one century."
</P>
<P>
Khamenei lashed out at the U.S. Administration and U.S. media
for "making hue and cry" over Khatami's interview with the Cable
News Network (CNN) last week, rejecting "the claims that Khatami's
remarks indicated Iran's demand for resumption of ties with the
United States."
</P>
<P>
"The claims are baseless and cruel to the Iranian nation
and President Khatami," he said, adding that "the Iranian
nation, the youth in particular, should realize the real goals
of this kind of dangerous propaganda and should be cautious
to the actions of the enemies."
</P>
<P>
He lauded Khatami for his statement that "we feel no need to
have relations with the U.S.," saying that the president well
explained all the principled stances of the country, particularly
Iran's ties with the U.S. and the issue of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei noted that there were some evil objectives behind the
"hue and cry" of the U.S. officials and media, saying that the
U.S. Administration intends to create differences among Iranian
officials in order to damage the Iranian nation.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is important for the U.S. to bring Iran to the
negotiation table, because Washington wants to create a uni-polar
world and wanted to be the leader of the world while "Iran is the
only country that does not submit itself to the U.S.."
</P>
<P>
He termed Iran and the United States as two rival polars
during the past two decades, saying that Tehran-Washington talks
are important for the U.S. because "it wanted to show that the
polar of the Islamic resistance failed in the confrontation."
</P>
<P>
He regarded the severance of diplomatic relations between Iran
and the U.S. as "natural result of the U.S. cruel behaviors" in
Iran, lauding the Iranian students who occupied the U.S. embassy
in Tehran in November, 1979.
</P>
<P>
He also attacked Washington for its support to Israel, saying
that "the Israeli regime, as what President Khatami said, is a
terrorist state and the U.S. support for such a state is enough
for Iranian nation to fight against it."
</P>
<P>
Khamenei also rejected that claims that the problems and
difficulties Iran is facing are the result of the severance of
Tehran-Washington relations, saying that facts show that talks and
ties with the U.S. would never solve the problems and difficulties
in Iran.
</P>
<P>
He termed the U.S. efforts to isolate Iran as a "failure,"
stressing that the efforts to isolate Iran would never have effect.
</P>
<P>
However, like Khatami, the Iranian leader also stressed that
Iran is not against the American nation, but the
U.S. Administration, saying that "we have repeatedly stated the
U.S. government, not the American people, is the enemy of the
Iranian country, nation and the Islamic system."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the strong words of Iranian leader
indicated a dark future for any rapprochement between the two
sworn enemies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
