<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Importer in China Ordered to Pay Compensatory Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A company that imported waste
products from outside China was ordered by a court in the eastern
Chinese province of Shandong today to pay 124,920 US dollars in
compensation for losses suffered by a shipping company.
</P>
<P>
The importer, Shandong Weifang Fuxiang Paper Co. Ltd, was
discovered in June 1996 to be importing containers of wastes from
the U.S. that could pollute the environment. It issued a statement
saying that it was giving up the practice, and left the waste at
an international goods distribution center for more than a year
and a half.
</P>
<P>
The shipper, the China Ocean-Going Shipping (Group) Corp., then
filed a lawsuit against the company, and an investigation revealed
that the wastes included surgical gowns and gloves, shoes,
stockings, cans, clothes hangers, bottles, plastic buckets, and
bags.
</P>
<P>
Fuxiang Paper left the imported items on center's grounds
saying that they were not the same as the items listed in the
contract.
</P>
<P>
According to today's verdict, Fuxiang Paper must remove the
items from the plaintiff's property within ten days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
