<HEADLINE> Telekom Achieves Big Profits, But Short of Expectation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Deutsche Telekom Friday reported
it achieved 3.3 billion marks (1.8 billion U.S. dollars) in
profits last year, up strongly from the 1.8 billion marks (1.0
billion dollars) in 1996, lower, however, than earlier expected.
</P>
<P>
Telekom previously projected that profits would come to 5 billion
marks (2.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figures, which Telekom said were preliminary, showed that group
turnover for 1997 reached 67.1 billion marks (36.6 billion dollars),
up 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the company attributed the results to good
performance in all its sectors, noting a 40 percent rise in
ISDN (integrated services digital network) sales and a 35 percent
increase in mobile phone sales.
</P>
<P>
Telekom planned to reduce its workforce to 170,000 by the end
of 2000 from 191,000 currently. In 1995, the company had 230,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Telekom said that its productivity per employee rose
by 12.5 percent to 342 marks (187 dollars) last year.  
</P>
