<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Products Prices Hiked in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' energy
authorities on Friday finally agreed to hike the prices of
petroleum products by an average 6.2 percent to avert a petroleum
product shortage in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Regulatory Board under the Department of Energy said
in an order that the prices of all oil products but liquefied
petroleum gas will be raised as of Friday afternoon by an average
of 0.53 pesos (1.3 U.S. cents) per liter.
</P>
<P>
The board said that the issuance of the provisional authority
for the country's three major oil firms to increase petroleum
prices was needed to ensure that the public get an adequate supply
of petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The country's three oil firms -- Petron, Pilipinas Shell and
Caltex
-- earlier warned in their petition filed to the board that their
ability to absorb the losses due to the peso depreciation has
reached "a critical point."
</P>
<P>
The three firms said they could no longer guarantee their
capacity to maintain full supply levels to homes and industries.
</P>
<P>
They had already stopped importation of crude oil and refined
oil products last month after the Energy Regulatory Board rejected
their requests to hike oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso has so far lost more than 50 percent in its
value against the U.S. dollar since its de facto devaluation in
July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil companies were stripped of the right to
determine oil prices in November last year after the Supreme Court
abolished the nine-month-old oil deregulation law designed to
liberalize the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Regulatory Board had repeatedly rejected the demand
for oil price hikes for fears of massive protests by labor
organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
