<HEADLINE> Mkapa Urges Improvement of Road Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has urged traffic authorities in his country to
take stricter measures to stop road accidents.
</P>
<P>
In a message of condolences sent Thursday to the bereaved
families of 25 people killed in a bus accident Wednesday, Mkapa
called on people to cooperate with the authorities in combating
dangerous driving, press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
"You should report to the police reckless bus drivers," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the message, the president said it is "disheartening" to
note that innocent Tanzanians continued to perish in road
accidents.
</P>
<P>
Police said the driver of the bus was driving at high speed
competing with another bus before it overturned, resulting the
death toll of 25 people.
</P>
<P>
Drivers of both buses escaped unhurt and they are being
questioned by the police.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Fredrick T. Sumaye said he was
shocked by the accident, the worst this year.
</P>
<P>
It is also Tanzania's worst traffic accident in the last three
months. On November 16 last year, a mini-bus driving at high
speed hit the road embankment in the northern region of Mara,
killing 17 people and seriously injuring eight others.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicated that between January and September last
year, 1,249 people were killed and 10,195 others injured in
11,420 road and railway accidents.
</P>
<P>
The government has repeatedly called for an end of driving
with overspeed, but only to the deaf ear of a number of drivers.
The traffic authorities have even equipped buses with speed
limits in an attempt to reduce the driving speed. However,
drivers play tricks to tamper with the devices.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Tanzanian Licensing Authority announced to
suspend transport licenses of 46 bus drivers who were found to be
driving with tampered limits, for three months beginning January
12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
