<HEADLINE> Reserve Bank of India Raises Bank Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) Friday increased the bank rate and the cash reserve ratio
(CRR) by two percent and 0.5 percent respectively to stem the fall
of the Indian currency rupee against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
Bank rate was hiked from 9 to 11 percent and CRR from 10 to
10.5 percent to be effective from Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This is the second package of monetary measures announced by
the RBI in more than one month. On December 2 the RBI announced
its first set of measures to calm foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate surcharge on import finance has been doubled from
15 percent to 30 percent in a move to subdue utilization of import
credit.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister P. Chidambaram said here Friday the RBI
package announced in the context of the continuous fall in the
rupee against the dollar will help bring about a considerable
degree of stability in the foreign exchange market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
