<HEADLINE> WHO: Influenza A Virus Found in Ducks, Geese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Influenza Type A (H5N1)
Virus has also been isolated in ducks and geese in Hong Kong,
China. The virus had formerly been found only in chickens, the
World Health Organization (WHO) announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
WHO said results of the research were released by a joint team
of scientists from WHO and Hong Kong University.
</P>
<P>
The positive culture samples were taken from wild and domestic
ducks and wild geese collected at markets in Hong Kong before the
slaughter of about 1.6 million chickens and other birds in early
January, it added.
</P>
<P>
However, WHO pointed out, the results do not yet allow for a
definitive determination of the initial source of the H5N1 virus.
</P>
<P>
"They also do not indicate whether domestic ducks raised on
farms in Hong Kong have to date been infected with the H5N1
virus," said WHO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
