<HEADLINE> China's Vice-Premier Points to Importance Of Customs Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The role of customs offices
must be increased as China increases its market economy changes and
opens widers to the rest of the world, Vice-premier Li Langqing
told a national meeting of customs directors today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the meeting, Li, who is a member of the Standing
Committee of the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China, told customs officials and personnel
that they should be effective in carrying out their
duties to make sure the state import and export policies
are implemented.
</P>
<P>
A greater effort should be made in collecting customs duties,
increasing supervisory work, and cracking down on smuggling and
other illegal activities, Li said, adding that reforms must be
brought to a new level.
</P>
<P>
He praised the contribution of customs offices last year in
increasing national fiscal well-being and safeguarding the entry
and exit work. Chinese customs collected 97.86 billion yuan in
customs duties, fines, and other administrative fees in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China plans to establish a more modern framework for its
customs system in about five years. 
</P>
