<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Calls on Tackling Teachers' Housing Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing has
called on central and local government departments to speed up the
work of tackling the housing problem for teachers, especially
younger teachers.
</P>
<P>
The problem should be solved within a couple of years, Li, who
is a member of the Standing Committee of the Communist Party of
China Central Committee Politburo, told a national conference in
Nanjing, capital of Jiangsu Province, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that this is a clear demonstration of the strategy of
"rejuvenating the nation by developing science and education" and
is a matter of showing respect to teachers.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the General Office of the State Council has held
the national conference every year to push its agenda, the
vice-premier said, and in the last four years, a lot of experience
has been gained through joint efforts of central and local
departments.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Nanjing, Li visited several teachers housing
and said he was glad to see them living in houses with each family
having more than 100 square meters.
</P>
<P>
University teachers' housing has lagged behind other
development, and of the 180,000 families with a poor housing, the
majority are young, Li said, adding that this problem must be
solved in major universities. 
