<HEADLINE> S'pore Welcomes Agreement Between Indonesia, IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government said
on Friday that it welcomed the latest agreement between Indonesia
and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued Friday night, the Prime Minister's
Office said Singapore welcomes the latest agreement between
Indonesia and the IMF, as the revised program will introduce
sweeping economic reforms and strengthen the Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
"It is a rigorous program," the Prime Minister's Office said.
Indonesian President Soeharto signed the second Letter of Intent
with the IMF on Thursday in order to overcome the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
And in line with a pledge to prioritize government spending,
several infrastructure projects now on hold will be canceled
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office said that by signing the Letter of
Intent himself, and chairing the high council to oversee the
implementation of the program, President Soeharto has signaled his
determination to take the hard decisions and implement them.
</P>
<P>
"President Soeharto assured Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong when
they met on January 13 in Jakarta that he would go through with
the IMF reforms. Prime Minister Goh felt that the president was
determined to bite the bullet this time," the statement said.
</P>
