<HEADLINE> Chinese Sweep Top Two in Women's Individual Medley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China's world record holder Wu
Yanyan led her teammate and best friend Chen Yan to a 1-2 finish
at the women's 200m individual medley final of the world swimming
championships on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wu, 20, clocked two minutes and 10.88 seconds, 0.91 seconds
better than the 16-year-old championship record but 1.16 seconds
outside of her world mark of 2:09.72 set in the Chinese National
Games last year.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Chen, new world champion in both the 400m
freestyle and 400m individual medley, touched home in 2:13.66,
0.60 seconds clear of Martina Moravcova of Slovakia who came third.
</P>
<P>
"I swam my best and I am very delighted to become world
champion," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
Chen came short of joining Australian Michael Klim as triple
gold medalist in swimming, but she was not unhappy. Only American
Jenny Thompson has won more gold than Klim.
</P>
<P>
"Wu is my best friend," Chen said. "I'm as happy as she is."
</P>
<P>
"Anyway, the 200m medley is not my speciality," Chen added.
</P>
<P>
Klim, who had won two gold medals and as many silver going into
Friday's 100m butterfly, splashed home first in his favored event
with a clocking of 52.25 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Lars Frolander got the silver medal in 52.79 and
Australian Geoff Huegill took the bronze in 52.90.
</P>
<P>
World top-ranked American Kurt Grote snatched the men's 200m
freestyle title, clocking 2:13.40.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Jean-Christophe Sarnin came second in 2:13.42, with
Hungary's Norbert Rozsa in third place in 2:13.59.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 4x100m medley relay, Jenny Thompson grabbed her
fourth title here as she led Lea Maurer, Kristy Kowal and Amy van
Dyken to the top of podium.
</P>
<P>
The American quartet timed 4:01.93, 3.19 seconds clear of
second-placed Australia. Japan got the bronze medal in 4:06.27.
</P>
<P>
Olena Zhupyna made it a golden double on Friday, winning the
women's platform synchronized diving.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Zhupyna, the 3m springboard gold medalist,
combined with fellow Ukrainian Svitlana Serbina to get a winning
total of 278.28 points from five dives.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese duo of Chen Li and Cai Yuyan, which scored just
1.74 points less, had to settle for the silver medal.
</P>
<P>
The American team of Kristin Link and Long Lindsay took the
bronze with 265.47 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
