<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US-led UN Arms Inspection Team Leaves Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Arms inspection team
headed by American Scott Ritter left Baghdad Friday after Iraq has
blocked it from carrying out missions for two consecutive days on
the ground that the composition of the team lacks balance.
</P>
<P>
Ritter, head of the 16-member U.N. arms inspection team,
including nine Americans and five Britons, held a news conference
Friday outside the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq
(UNSCOM) headquarters in Baghdad before they left here.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be back," said Ritter, who was accused by Iraq of an
American spy. He added that "the departure of this team in no way
reflects a change in UNSCOM's determination to conduct
inspections."
</P>
<P>
Iraq barred the team, which arrived in Baghdad on Monday, from
carrying out its work from Tuesday on the ground that the
composition of this team does not reflect a balanced
participation of permanent members of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"It's time for us to leave and let the business of what is
going to happen next go to the (UNSCOM) executive chairman." said
Ritter.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, the chief U.N. arms inspector, will visit
Baghdad on January 19-21 to hold talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz on the issue of U.N. inspectors' access to
Iraqi presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM decided on Thursday to withdraw Ritter's team a day
earlier than scheduled. The team was supposed to leave on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The team was blocked on Tuesday and Wednesday from carrying
out its work and after orders from Butler they did not make
another attempt on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Other U.N. inspectors have been able to carry out their work
with no limitations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
