<HEADLINE> South Korea's Auto Sales Up 23.8 Percent in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korea sold a total of
95,083 cars in Australia in 1997, a 23.8 percent jump over the
previous year, the Korea Trade-Investment Promotion Agency
(KOTRA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jeeps and station wagons also enjoyed increasing sales, with
5,111 units sold, soaring 523.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
KOTRA attributed the rise in recreational vehicle sales to the
launch of Kia Sportage as well as the popularity of Ssangyong
Musso.
</P>
<P>
Along with increasing sales, South Korea's share in the
Australian car market also climbed by 1.3 percentage points to
17.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Its share in the van and wagon market also grew 2.7 percentage
points to 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kia Pride enjoyed the largest selling among mini cars,
dominating 28.8 percent of the market. Hyundai Excel and Coupe
ranked as the best selling cars in the sub-compact and sports car
divisions respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Sonata was the third biggest selling car after the
Toyota Camry and the Honda Prelude. 
</P>
</TEXT>
