<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans To Reform Publishing, Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China plans to make the press
and the publishing business more market oriented and
industrialized, according to a national press and publications
conference that opened here today.
</P>
<P>
It was decided that publishing houses would be made more
efficient and management and operations improved. China will also
establish some publishing and newspaper groups.
</P>
<P>
China's publishing houses and big bookstores are all run by the
state and the planned economy has long been their mode of
operation. So, bookstores at the county level will be introduced
to the leasing, contract, share holding, and cooperative system to
topple the old form of ownership, and chain stores will be
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, it was decided that some state-owned printing
houses will become companies and some newspapers will be selected
for management reforms on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
China is a publishing giant, releasing more than 100,000 titles
annually, but many of them are poorly written and do not appeal to
readers, because market needs are seldom considered.
</P>
<P>
Although the sector will become more industrialized and market
oriented in the future, moral and social effect will still be a
major consideration, according to Yu Youxian, director of the
Press and Publications Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Banker Says Asian Crisis Won't End in 6 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- President of the French banking
group Paribas, Andre Levy-Lang, said Friday that it is not likely
the Asian financial crisis will end in six months.
</P>
<P>
``This is a crisis of rebounding. It will mark the year 1998,''
Levy-Lang said in the French economic daily La Tribune.
</P>
<P>
He said Paribas began to exercise prudence in Asian investments
beginning in 1997. In 1997, the organization invested 9 billion
U.S. dollars in Asian countries, excluding Japan, and 4.5 billion
francs (750 million dollars) in Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
Other French commercial banks, such as La Societe Generale, le
Credit Lyonnais, and the Bank Nationale de Paris (BNP) have also
invested heavily in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
