<HEADLINE> Chinese Top Official Condemns Doping Offences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Li Tieying, member of the
Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party's Central
Committee and state concilor, strongly condemned the ugly doping
offences here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of directors of the provincial sports
committees, Li Tieying said the drug cases at the World Swimming
Championships damaged the image of the Chinese sports.
</P>
<P>
The International Swimming Federation announced on January 11
four Chinese swimmers were tested positive in their A samples in
an out-of-competition test at the World Swimming Championships in
Perth, Australia, and a swimmer and her coach were caught of
trafficking in banned substances by the Sydney Customs on January
8.
</P>
<P>
Li Tieying said drug abuse is a kind of corruption and
immorality in sports. The scandal smeared the reputation of the
Chinese sports.
</P>
<P>
The annual meeting of the directors of the provincial sports
committees and organizations started on January 12 and ended here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Li said to the delegates that it is a long-term struggle to
fight against drug abuses in sports and the stance of the Chinese
government against doping is firm, unequivocal and persistant.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government firmly supports the principle and
unremitting efforts of the Chinese Olympic Committee in the
anti-doping campaign," he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Chinese sports fields should implement
the strictest and the most effective measures in the fight against
doping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
