<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Chinese Satisfied with Their Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A survey has shown that most
Chinese believe the society of China is stable and more than 80
percent of them are satisfied with their lives.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences (CASS), reports that government officials regard
sustained economic development, political stability and improved
living standards are the criteria of a stable society, and the
rapid economic development and low inflation in 1997 provided a
basis for that.
</P>
<P>
Officials and experts from some 20 government departments and
academic institutions discussed some of these at a meeting today.
</P>
<P>
They say that 112 million people have bought pension insurance
policies and 206 cities have established a minimum wage system to
guarantee a certain income.
</P>
<P>
Income of urban and rural people in 1997 were up seven percent
on 1996 and bank deposits were up 18 percent. Economists estimate
that the amount of capital and assets held by ordinary Chinese has
grown to 7 trillion yuan (870 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The improvements in living standards and market supply have
made the society even more stable, says Li Peilin, a sociologist,
who participated in the survey. Li attributed this to
urbanization, changes in employment, fewer crimes, and the return
of Hong Kong to the motherland, which has increased the Chinese
people's national pride.
</P>
<P>
However, experts say that unemployment is still a major
problem which, coupled with social welfare and the reform in
state-owned enterprises, is causing public concern.
</P>
<P>
The CASS researchers suggest that the macro-economic control be
maintained in 1998, and the reform of the social welfare system be
stepped up.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
