<HEADLINE> Macao to Issue "Year of Tiger" Stamps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Macao is to issue a set of new
stamps featuring the "Lunar Year of the Tiger" in 1998 on Sunday
to mark the Chinese lunar year, a Macao posts official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Lopes, director of the Macao Posts and
Telecommunications Department (CTT), announced at a press
conference on Friday that a total of 2.3 million pieces of the new
stamps, with a face value of 5.5 patacas (0.69 US dollars), will be
issued.
</P>
<P>
Legend has it that tiger was fundamentally a terrifying entity
in ancient China. Its mask would repel the malignant spirits or
demons; thus it was displayed at the courts' doors to drive away
the spirits of injustice and of corruption. Its power as a guard
could also be witnessed in the stone sculptures placed by graves.
</P>
<P>
Collection of such stamps issued in Macao has become
increasingly popular. Macao issued 500,000 pieces of stamps for
the Year of the Rat in 1996, and 1.5 million pieces for the Year
of Ox in 1997. Officials said that the demand may outnumber the
planned 2.3 million this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 13 sets of stamps were issued last year,
contributing about 200 million patacas of gross income for
CTT. Lopes said that his department has decided to raise the
benchmark of each new issue from 1.5 million pieces in 1997 to
2.1 million pieces this year to meet increasing demand of Macao
stamps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
