<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Trade Secretary Vows to Build Strong Ties With Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The British Government is
"absolutely determined" to build a strong and close relationship
at every level with the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) of China, a senior British trade official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon organized by the British Chamber of
Commerce in Hong Kong, Margaret Beckett, president of the British
Board of Trade, said that although Britain's political
relationship with Hong Kong changed on July 1, 1997, all those
other links which have bound Britain and Hong Kong together remain
firmly in place.
</P>
<P>
These include the business links and the massive levels of
British investment in Hong Kong, said Beckett, who arrived in Hong
Kong Thursday for a four-day visit following her trips to Beijing
and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Two way trade flows between Britain and Hong Kong are now
running at over seven billion pounds (about 11.3 billion U.S.
dollars) per year. Hong Kong is now Britain's 12th largest export
market.
</P>
<P>
Total British investment in Hong Kong now stands at over 145.4
billion Hong Kong dollars (18.64 billion U.S. dollars) and
accounts for over 25 percent of all external investment in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
There are around 1,000 British companies with offices in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
"These are staggering figures which indisputably make Hong Kong
the most important hub for British business in Asia," Beckett
said.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that our commercial links will deepen and grow
over the coming years," she added.
</P>
<P>
Beckett said that while there may continue to be difficult
times ahead for Hong Kong, Britain's confidence in Hong Kong's
strong economic fundamentals remains undiminished.
</P>
<P>
Whilst the Asian financial crisis may have impacted upon Hong
Kong's own prospects for growth in the short term, what has been
impressive has been the robust way in which it has been handled by
the authorities here, Beckett said.
</P>
<P>
She recalled that when British Prime Minister Tony Blair met
Chinese President Jiang Zemin in Hong Kong last June Blair said
that Britain saw the transfer of Hong Kong as a bridge not a
barrier to its future relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
"What struck me most during my recent visit to Beijing and
Shanghai was the genuine enthusiasm amongst Chinese leaders for a
strong and positive business relationship with Britain," Beckett
told members of the British Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The size of China's economy and its ability to maintain
manageable and sustainable growth rates whilst bringing inflation
down to low single figures means it is a market which any British
company that is serious about a long term exporting strategy
cannot afford to ignore.
</P>
<P>
"In this respect the role of Hong Kong is particularly
important," Beckett said.
</P>
<P>
"I should also say how much we in Britain have been encouraged
and heartened by the recent clear public affirmations by senior
Chinese leaders that they are fully committed to the principle of
'one country, two systems' as enshrined in the Joint Declaration,"
Beckett said. She added that this gives a strong boost to
confidence in Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
Friday morning, Beckett opened the 1998 British Education
Festival at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the festival, Beckett said
that it was a great pleasure for her to be in Hong Kong just
over six months after the handover and she was delighted to see
how smooth the transition has been.
</P>
<P>
Beckett was scheduled to meet Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China, Friday
afternoon and visit the new airport at Chek Lap Kok Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
