<HEADLINE> Enterprises Propose Action to Protect Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- An environmental official has
called on Chinese society to pay serious attention to the
worsening pollution problems along the Yangtze River, the
country's longest river.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come for the country to effectively control
pollution along the Yangtze in order to avoid repeating the
ill-fated Huaihe River," according to Yang Zhenghuai, vice
director of the Environment and Resources Protection Committee of
the National People's Congress, China's top legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Yang was in Wuhan to preside over a meeting on protecting
Yangtze River water resources. Some 30 large enterprises attending
the meeting which ended yesterday, including the Wuhan Iron and
Steel Corp. and Yangtze Petrochemical Corp., proposed that
factories and enterprises along the river protect related
resources "as if they were protecting their mothers" and to strive
to ensure a pollution-free Yangtze in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River, the third longest river in the world, flows
from the west to the east and meanders through 11 provinces and
autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the National Environmental Protection Agency
(NEPA) show that some 15 billion tons of waste waster are
discharged into the river annually.
</P>
<P>
Despite the relatively good water quality in the mainstream of
the river, a pollution belt stretching 565 km. has formed between
25 coastal cities, with increasing water contamination in many
areas.
</P>
<P>
"The dry-up in various sections of the Yellow River and
serious pollution problems along the Huaihe River have sounded alarm
bells. We cannot afford to delay efforts to save the Yangtze
River," said Yang, who also expressed his appreciation for the
proposal tabled by enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The proposal calls for gradually readjusting industrial and
production structures, introducing advanced technology, promoting
clean production and reducing discharges to a minimum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0140 </DOCNO>
