<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Does Not Need IMF Programs to Recover Its </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia does not need
International Monetary Fund (IMF) programs to help its economy to
recover, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has a strong economic fundamentals and in the past few
months the authorities have taken important preemptive measures to
address the situation, particularly on the fiscal side, Camdessus
said at a news conference at the end of his two-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said he applauded the measures notably in the
economic package announced by Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister
Anwar Ibrahim last month.
</P>
<P>
The austerity measures announced by Anwar include scaling down
of economic growth from seven percent to between four and five
percent, deferring large projects, cutting government expenditure
by 18 percent, curbing credit growth and ensuring loans for
productive sectors only.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief was of the view that Malaysia's financial
position was strong and there was no need to raise taxes and that
the country's fiscal position was also sufficiently strong.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there was a need for Malaysia to continue
strengthening its policies, particularly on the monetary side, to
achieve a better policy mix in efforts to secure market confidence
given the volatile currency markets and exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia does not need a Fund (IMF) program to achieve this.
Our strategy is to help Malaysia as much as Malaysia wishes to
continue solving its problems on its own," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the IMF team, which is here for consultations,
would come back in March to further discuss the implementation of
the tough measures that Malaysia has taken so far.
</P>
<P>
To a question on the structural reforms that Malaysia could
undertake, the IMF chief said the system of control of prices of
goods as well as intervention by the government in certain
economic areas "certainly has to be re-analyzed and possibly
canceled."
</P>
<P>
On Malaysia's proposed mergers of local financial institutions,
Camdessus welcomed the move as it would lead to reinforcing their
positions and increasing their competitive edge when the local
financial market was further liberalized.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus told reporters the reforms being taken by the
affected regional economies such as Indonesia, South Korea and
Thailand with the IMF assistance.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said he was pretty certain that it would take about
two and a half years for the countries in the region to recover
back to their high growth in a more sustainable way and eventually
put them in a better position.
</P>
<P>
"Our work is to help countries to establish confidence among
international investors...this is in our chapter but not in
whatever miracle way...we help them in their policies and
reestablish confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, who flew in from Indonesia Thursday afternoon, met
Mahathir Friday and Anwar Thursday evening to discuss the current
economic problems facing several Asian countries, including
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is visiting a number of Asian countries, including
South Korea, in efforts to mitigate the economic crisis facing the
region.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is leaving for Singapore later Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
