<HEADLINE> Chinese Academy Expands International Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CASS) sent 5,100 people to study or work overseas, and hosted
visits by 2,050 foreign scholars and officials during 1997,
according to CAAS President Lu Yongxiang.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign-funded cooperative projects also grew,
with foreign partners providing 89 million yuan in funding and
scientific equipment, some 50 percent of which came from Japan,
said Lu.
</P>
<P>
Financial aid from international organizations enabled CAAS
members to attend international symposia and launch new research
projects, said Lu, adding that the CAAS has expanded cooperation
with enterprises in a number of countries and regions, including
Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Lu said China's resumption of sovereignty over Hong Kong has
greatly promoted cooperation with universities and institutes in
the new administrative region. More than 800 CAAS members visited
Hong Kong to participate in various projects during 1997. In
addition, the CAAS and universities in Hong Kong jointly
established laboratories in wide-ranging fields, including the
life sciences, bioengineering and information sciences.
</P>
<P>
The CAAS also developed scientific cooperation with
institutions in Taiwan. Some 180 members visited Taiwan for short
visits, with additional 20 members working on mid- to long-term
projects. The academy hosted visits by more than 400 scholars
and researchers from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The CAAS plans to invite 100 foreign scholars to work in the
academy during 1998, said Lu. 
</P>
