<HEADLINE> HK Government Secretariat To Be Relocated at Waterfront Tamar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Tamar basin reclamation
site will be withdrawn from the land sales program and be
earmarked for relocating the existing Government Secretariat,
Secretary for Planning, Environment and Lands Bowen Leung said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The site, located between the Prince of Wales Building and the
CITIC Tower, occupies an area of 2.56 hectares on the waterfront
of Victoria Harbor. About half of the site was scheduled for
auction in March 1998 under the 1997/1998 Land Sales Program.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that the Government Secretariat located in the
Central Government Offices at Lower Albert Road and Murray
Building at Garden Road has been experiencing a severe shortage of
space for some years.
</P>
<P>
"A number of bureaux are now housed elsewhere in Central or
Wanchai," he added.
</P>
<P>
"In order to meet present and future needs for office space and
the new requirement as a Special Administrative Region, the
government has been searching for some time for a suitable site
for relocating the Government Secretariat," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Tamar site has now been identified as the most suitable
site and will therefore be withdrawn from sale.
</P>
<P>
The sites occupied by the existing Central Government Offices
and Murray Building have a total area of 2.43 hectares. They will
be considered for commercial use after the relocation of the
Government Secretariat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
