<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Appoints Members to New Strategic Development Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region government announced in a statement here on
Friday that it had appointed members of a newly established
advisory body to Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
The Commission on Strategic Development was set up following
Tung's announcement in his Policy Address made in October last
year.
</P>
<P>
The Commission will advise Chief Executive on long-term
development issues. It will be tasked with conducting reviews and
studies on the development needs and goals on issues such as the
local economy, human resources, education, housing, land supply,
environment and relations with China's inland.
</P>
<P>
The Commission's objective is to ensure that Hong Kong's
limited resources be well-used, Hong Kong remains competitive and
keeps the validity of its economic development, the government
said.
</P>
<P>
The members of the body include Chief Secretary for
Administration Anson Chan, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang,
Executive Council Convenor S.Y. Chung, provisional legislator
Cheng Yiu-tong, some businessmen and the president of the Chinese
University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive is pleased that the newly established body
can benefit from the expertise and advice of such prominent
persons in the community. Additional members will be co-opted
depending on the issues to be discussed, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
And an international panel of experts will also be appointed to
assist the Commission in formulating recommendations, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Commission is expected to have its first meeting in
February this year, according to the statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
