<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
National Defense held a grand party tonight to mark the upcoming
Chinese lunar new year of the Tiger.
</P>
<P>
Attending the party were Chi Haotian, vice-chairman of the
Central Military Commission (CMC), State Councillor and defense
minister, Fu Quanyou, member of CMC and chief of general staff, Yu
Yongbo, member of CMC and director of the PLA General Political
Department, Wang Ke, member of CMC and director of the PLA General
Logistics Department and dozens of senior PLA officers, as well as
military attaches and deputy military attaches of foreign
countries in China.
</P>
<P>
Luo Bin, director of the Foreign Affairs Office of the Defense
Ministry, addressed the party on behalf of Chi Haotian. He
described 1997 as an extraordinary year in which the Chinese
People's Liberation (PLA) celebrated the 70th anniversary of its
founding and Chinese troops were smoothly stationed in Hong Kong
after China resumes the exercise of its sovereignty over it.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the year, his office also conducted a
series of activities for foreign military attaches in China, which
had helped them gain a better understanding of China's national
conditions and China's domestic and foreign policies, as well as
PLA's history, nature and tasks.
</P>
<P>
Luo also thanked the military attaches for their effective work
in helping enhance mutual understanding between Chinese and
foreign armed forces and their friendly cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The PLA was active in its overseas exchanges in the past
year. The Sino-foreign exchanges and cooperation between Chinese
and foreign armed forces helped advance the relations between
respective countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, PLA hosted 156 military delegations
from 67 countries in 1997 and also sent 86 delegations or groups
to 66 countries.
</P>
<P>
Luo promised that his office would continue to increase PLA's
exchanges and cooperation with foreign armies on the basis of the
Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence. 
</P>
