<HEADLINE> Fund to Upgrade Fire Safety Gear in HK Old Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A 200 million HK dollar (25.6
million U.S. dollars) fund will be created to help owners of Hong
Kong's old commercial buildings modernize fire safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
Owners of some 400 pre-1973 commercial buildings here are
thought to be the first batch of borrowers for the Fire
Improvement Fund.
</P>
<P>
No detailed criteria or ceiling for the fund has been fixed,
according to Deputy Secretary of Security Alex Fong Chi-wai.
</P>
<P>
Legislators' approval of the fund will be sought in March and
an advisory committee will be set up to vet loan applicants and
oversee the fund's revolving operation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Potential borrowers also include owners of some of the 500
commercial buildings required to upgrade fire safety equipment by
a law proposed in 1994. The law, enacted last May, will be
extended to all 400 pre-1973 commercial buildings under the Fire
Safety Bill 1998 approved by the Executive Council of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region government.
</P>
<P>
Government officials hope to have the upgrading of the 400
blocks completed within three years.
</P>
<P>
Poor safety status in many of the old commercial buildings
poses great hazards to local residents. A blaze in the Garley
Building in Kowloon in November 1996, believed to be the worst
fire in Hong Kong over the past century, left 39 people dead and
81 injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
