<HEADLINE> Urgent: Iranian Leader Rejects Talks with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei Friday rejects any talks and ties with
the United States, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei made the remark at the Friday prayer congregation. He
said that any talks and ties with the "great Satan," the United
States, would be harmful to the Iranian nation.
</P>
<P>
"We feel no need to have relations with the United States, the
(Iranian) President (Mohammad Khatami) made a right statement" in
his recent interview with the American Cable News Network, Khamenei
said.
</P>
<P>
Lauding Khatami for his statement about the U.S. crimes against
the Iranian nation during the past half century, the Iranian
leader stated that "today Iran and the United States represent
two rival fronts, i.e. Islam and arrogance."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the strong words by the Iranian
leader indicated a dark future for any rapprochement between the
two sworn enemies, although Khatami called for cultural dialogue
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the United States severed diplomatic relations in 1980
after Iranian students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran.
</P>
</TEXT>
