<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Clean Up Kai Tak Airport Site for Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government has
decided to carry out a 60 million HK dollar (7.69 million U.S.
dollars) clean-up operation after the closure of the Kai Tak
Airport in July to prepare the site for development.
</P>
<P>
Investigations conducted by the Environmental Protection
Department at the Kai Tak Airport site have found leaks of
aviation fuel and other toxic pollutants under the north apron.
Aircraft fuel leakage is a common problem at airports worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The Kai Tak Airport is to be replaced by the new Hong Kong
International Airport at Chek Lap Kok, which is now under
construction and scheduled to open in July, and the government
plans to use the site for a housing project.
</P>
<P>
The pollutants identified in the soil and water in the area
include such toxic and inflammable substances as petroleum,
benzene and methane.
</P>
<P>
Exposure to these substances could prove hazardous to health
and may lead to cancer, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Volatile pollutants are to be extracted by blowing air into the
soil while less volatile pollutants will be injected with oxygen
to remove their toxicity.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes to begin its housing construction project
on the 154-hectare site at the airport's north apron in Kwon Bay
by 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
