<HEADLINE> Memorandum Calls for Enhanced Sino-Canadian Environmental Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Canadian
Environmental officials announced today that the two nations will
expand cooperation in the area of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of China's National Environmental
Protection Agency (NEPA), and Canadian Environmental Minister
Christine Stewart, renewed the Memorandum of Understanding on
Environmental Cooperation between the two agencies.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, which extends environmental cooperation into
the 21st century, calls for the two countries to mainly cooperate
in clean production methods and ecological protection over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
China and Canada have jointly conducted research related
to sustainable development and environmental education since the
original memorandum was signed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Senior leaders from the two nation's have engaged in frequent
exchange visits in recent years. The two sides have also recorded
notable achievements in controlling water pollution in the Huaihe
and Haihe river valleys, and environmental protection in Sichuan
and Shandong provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
