<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil leak Suspends Export in Southeast Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Exports of two cargoes of crude oil
from a terminal in southeast Nigeria's Akwa Ibom State were postponed
on Thursday due to the continued loss of 100,000 barrels per day of oil
by the world giant Mobil operating there.
</P>
<P>
The exact volume of crude shipment affected by the deferment is yet
to be ascertained but Mobil officials figured the company could have
already lost 2.1 million U.S.Dollars, according to press reports
today.
</P>
<P>
Mobil last month pushed oil output of the joint venture with the
Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation to 700,000 barrels per day. It
now has the production slashed to 600,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
But officials said the joint venture's target of hitting an output
level of 900,000 barrels per day in the next two years still remained
on course.
</P>
<P>
Mobil reported an oil spill of about 40,000 barrels resulting from
a leak in a pipeline running between a production platform and the Qua
Iboe terminal earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The affected 24-inch pipeline was installed in 1971 and was last
certified on May 1, 1991 for a period of 20 years up to 2011.
</P>
<P>
By Thursday, more than half of the oil spill had been cleaned up,
while the slick formed by the spill on the ocean had started clearing
away, companies sources said.
</P>
<P>
The leaking pipeline is regarded to have precipitated the single
largest oil spill in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mobil officials said that the company is battling to have the spill
under control and minimize the impact on the environment, where
additional dispersant and equipment have been ordered from abroad.
</P>
<P>
The last incident of suspension in Nigeria's oil delivery was in
1994, when Shell Petroleum Development Company was constrained by an
oil workers strike to do so.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
