<HEADLINE> S.African Security Chiefs Discuss Cross-Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The defence and security
ministers from Zimbabwe, Angola, Malawi, Namibia, South Africa
and Zambia met here Thursday to discuss issues relating to
cross-border criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
including arms smuggling, drug trafficking, money laundering
and air space violations by individuals and companies.
</P>
<P>
A communique released at the end of the one-day meeting said
ministers of state security, defence and home affairs from the
six southern African countries also discussed the issue of
individuals or companies which facilitated logistical
supplies to UNITA-held areas in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that six southern African countries who
are members of the Ad Hoc Committee of the Inter-State Defence
and Security Committee, took great exception to these criminal
activities and "strongly warn the individuals and companies
involved in the perpetration of these activities that from now on
they will do so at great risk of losing both their lives and
property."
</P>
<P>
The Ad Hoc Committee requested diplomatic missions in the region
to support its cause by disseminating information on the
issues discussed to their respective governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
