<HEADLINE> Boundary Street of Chung Ying Street in Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chung Ying Street, on the
border with Hong Kong's New Territories, has 10 or 20 thousand
visitors every day, not only to see its ancient sites, but also
the inexpensive fashionable goods.
</P>
<P>
Some come just to see the changes instead of shopping, as did a
group of tourists from Heilongjiang Province in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
There are banners flying above the street announcing its
presence, and there is an old landmark from the Qing Dynasty. The
Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress decided to
keep the name of the 250-meter street, which runs through
Shatoujiao Town.
</P>
<P>
It is known as "one street with two social systems" and is
marked by eight boundary tablets. Chinese armed police and Hong
Kong police patrol the street every day on their respective sides.
</P>
<P>
The government of Shatoujiao has organized many clean-up
operations on the street, and the local industrial and commercial
administration cracked down on fake goods being sold in shops on
the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen authorities intend to promote tourism, shopping and
entertainment along the street, local officials say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
