<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Share prices finished higher
as the strength in most regional stock markets lured buying on the
local bourse, with the Straits Times Industrials Index (STII)
reversing its early decline to end at 1245.26 points, up by 11.9
points.
</P>
<P>
The stability or firmness in regional currencies has also
stoked buying on the Singapore bourse, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Moderate bargain hunting by overseas funds shored up the
market, especially the banking and property stocks, which led the
market's advance, they added.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume stood at 266.48 million units, valued
at 476.08 million Singapore dollars (273.61 million US dollars).
Advances overwhelmed declines by 264 to 98, while 251 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Wing Tai was the most actively traded counter as it registered
a turnover of 18.91 million units. It was followed by Renong Bhd
which had 15.9 million shares traded. Singapore Telecom was next
with 14.16 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by one dollar to end at 23 Singapore dollars.
NBT increased by 67 cents to close at 3.62 Singapore dollars,
while KL Kepong gained 58 cents to finish at 3.38 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Heong Leong Ind. was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.08 dollars to close at 1.22 Singapore dollars. Ipco
Warrant fell by 27 cents to finish at 1.02 Singapore dollars.
Local car distributor Cycle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C) was 20 cents lower at
4.3 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
