<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12,999 More Chakma Refugees Return To Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 16 (Xinhua)-- 12,999 more Chakma refugees
have returned to their homeland in Bangladesh in the last
fortnight, official sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 25,285 Chakmas had been repatriated from India's
Tripura State Since 1994 to Chittagong Hill Tract of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
About 60,000 Bangladeshi tribals, mostly Chakmas, had crossed
over to Tripura on various occasions since April 1986, following
disturbances in the Chittagong Hill Tract areas.
</P>
<P>
The final phase of repatriation started following the assurance
by Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina to the Chakma leaders
that the 20-point agreement signed on March 9 last year in India's
Agartala would be implemented. Under the agreement, both India and
Bangladesh would provide some economic assistance to those
refugees who return to their homeland, the Bangladesh government
would ensure their safety after returning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Daily Oil Output to up 60,000 Barrels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's crude oil output is to
increase by 60,000 barrels a day following the start-up of oil
production in a new oil field late last month.
</P>
<P>
The Ofon Field, scheduled to go on stream this month, is jointly
developed by the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) and
the world oil giant Elf, at a cost of 300 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The production capacity of 60,000 barrels per day is to be attained
fully by the turn of the century, an equivalent of three percent to
the country's current daily total, the Daily Times reported today,
quoting Elf officials.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has projected a revenue of 9.833 billion
U.S. Dollars from crude oil in this year's budget, based on a
production level of 2.175 million barrels per day and official selling
price of 17 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The production capacity of the country however is expected to be on
the rise as Shell, which accounts for about 60 percent of Nigeria's
oil production, said two days ago that it might have a breakthrough in
production in deep offshore fields.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
