<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Gain 1.1 Percent on Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
bounced off morning lows to finish more than one percent higher
Friday after a healthy gain on Japan's key Nikkei index brought
some much-needed confidence back to the market.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index added 29.5 points to 2614.0 with the
market struggling off a poor performance on Wall Street overnight
where the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 92.92 points, or
1.19 percent, to 7691.77.
</P>
<P>
The Australian market opened near its low for the day of 2571.4
before bouncing back on higher Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones dealer Scott Emms said the rally also
had been fueled by overseas institutional buying.
</P>
<P>
"There's a bit of positive sentiment coming out of the Asian
markets," Emms said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished the day up 45.8 points at
4510.7 and the all resources was 17.2 points up at 1096.6.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Nikkei index surged 924.0 points to 16046.0 and Hong
Kong's Hang Seng climbed 264.5 points to 8843.4 in afternoon
trade.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 336.52 million shares valued at 846.44
million Australian dollars (550.18 million US dollars), with
rising stocks beating falling stocks by 549 to 477.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said one of the leading stocks behind the late rally
was Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., which rocketed to the 9.00
Australian dollars mark during the day before resting up 21.9
cents, or 2.52 percent stronger, at 8.91 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other major movers included retailer Woolworths, which was one
of the most heavily traded shares and rose 18 cents.
</P>
<P>
Analysts and brokers said Woolworths shares have been propelled
by growing investor-enthusiasm about the retailer's interim sales
results - due out next week - after Harvey Norman Holdings Lt.'s
buoyant result Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among the resource companies, BHP was 18 cents higher, MIM was
one cent stronger and Rio Tinto gained 54.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks also showed strong improvement thanks to a 5.90
rise in the gold bullion price. Bullion in Sydney closed at 287.75
US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
