<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Half US Cent Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar clawed
up by almost half an US cent Friday, inspired by a higher gold
price and improved Asian financial markets.
</P>
<P>
A fall in the US dollar against the Japanese yen also buoyed
the local dollar to end the week on a positive note.
</P>
<P>
The currency closed at 65.58 US cents, from 65.13 Thursday and
near its highs of the session.
</P>
<P>
Citibank Australia foreign exchange dealer Nigel Dobson said
there was a lot of two-way interest in the market.
</P>
<P>
"The yen strengthened overnight and I think that's indicative
of less negative sentiment coming out of Asia," Dobson said.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment in the region has been boosted by signs of an
improvement in the Asian crisis after the Indonesian government
and the IMF reached agreement on a revised reform program.
</P>
<P>
Reports that the Japanese Liberal Democratic Party may release
another economic stimulus package in March, featuring an extension
of the two trillion yen income tax cut to two to three years also
added support.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso, the South Korean won, the Taiwan dollar
and the Hong Kong dollar all strengthened Friday, counterbalancing
falls in the Indonesian rupiah, the Malaysian ringgit, the
Singapore dollar and the Thai baht.
</P>
<P>
The jump in the gold price provided further support for the
Australian dollar. Gold bullion in Sydney closed 5.25 higher at
287.75 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also ended at 84.02 yen from 85.13 and at
1.2021 marks from 1.1868. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
