<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sign Language Counted as Foreign Language on U.S. Campus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Under the new policy, approved by the university's committee on
undergraduate studies, students can earn course credit by studying
the sign language.
</P>
<P>
Stanford is one of a growing number of American colleges and
universities which formally accept ASL in the fulfillment of
foreign or second language requirements and give it a status
similar to that of the "traditional" foreign languages such as
French, Spanish, German, Chinese, Japanese and Russian.
</P>
<P>
ASL was developed by American deaf people to communicate with
each other.
</P>
<P>
Many students report that they take ASL specially to make them
better qualified or more competitive in the non-deafness related
careers.
</P>
<P>
ASL is now used by approximately 500,000 deaf people in the
United States and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
