<HEADLINE> Tianjin Witnesses Foreign Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The foreign trade volume of
Tianjin, the largest port city in north China, topped 10 billion
US dollars last year, up 28 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The figure included exports valued at 5.02 billion US dollars,
up 24 percent on 1996, and imports of 5.01 billion US dollars, a
rise of 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's foreign-funded enterprises recorded a substantial
rise in exports during the year, with their export volume of 3.1
billion US dollars, up 46 percent on 1996 and accounting for 63
percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the city has witnessed increasing exports of
machinery and electronic products represents a great change from
the past when major exports were farm and non-staple foodstuffs
and low value-added products.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's exported machinery and electronic products were
valued at 2.1 billion US dollars in 1997, up 39 percent on 1996
and accounting for 41 percent of the total local exports.
</P>
<P>
Local technology exports last year jumped 15 percent to 182
million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
