<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Face Severe Drought: Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam forecast that a large
part of the country is to face severe drought, according local
press reports Friday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast was made by the General Department of
Hydrometerology based on the fact that rain gauges recorded in
those localities since the beginning of the year were lower than
previous corresponding periods.
</P>
<P>
Warmer weather in many localities has caused much concern among
farmers about the approach of a drought.
</P>
<P>
Average temperature in the northern region stood at 21-22
Celsius degrees or six degrees higher than the average of previous
years and the highest recorded temperatures in the last 41 years.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's central and southern provinces have also suffered
from warmer weather.
</P>
<P>
Water levels in rivers and reservoirs across the country are
low, dropping between 10-20 percent in the north and 20-25 percent
in the central and central highland regions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile water levels in southern rivers have decreased by
0.4-0.5 meters compared to levels recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, the early intrusion of salt water to river mouths
is causing much concern among southern farmers.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's prime minister sent this week an official message,
requesting officials in the northern and northern central
provinces to map out effective measures to help farmers avoid crop
failure caused by warmer weather.
</P>
<P>
The message warned that transplanting over-mature rice
seedlings due to the prolonged warmer weather in the spring crop
would cause a sharp drop in rice yield. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
