<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Visit of Israeli Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi has denied the report that an Israeli
delegation had visited Iran, saying that Israel spread such rumors
in an effort to seek legitimation from Iran.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi Thursday termed the report about a visit of Israeli
technicians to Iran as "baseless rumors," according to Tehran
radio Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel made such baseless rumors about Israeli
demand for contacts with Iranian officials with the aim of
diverting the public opinion from Iran's anti-Israeli stance.
</P>
<P>
Iran has made several denials about contacts and cooperation
between Tehran and Tel Aviv since the beginning of this year,
saying that the reports were aimed at distorting Iran's image.
</P>
<P>
Tehran stressed that Iran would not recognize the Israeli
government due to its aggressive nature, calling on Islamic
countries to reconsider their relations with Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Iran broke off its diplomatic relations with Israel soon after
the Islamic Revolution in 1979, accusing Tel Aviv of occupying
Arab lands, particularly Jerusalem, the holy place for Muslims,
Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
However, media reports said that secret contacts and even
cooperation between the two sworn enemies had continued during the
past 18 years, although Iran repeatedly denied them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
