<HEADLINE> Poor Population Drops in North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.42 million
poor people in north China's Hebei Province rose above the
poverty line last year, a provincial official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The number of poverty-stricken people in Hebei has declined
from seven million to 2.44 million, or 4.6 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the success to financial aid and
technical guidance from other provinces.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 18 central government departments in Beijing
provided Hebei with a direct investment of 20 million yuan and
sent experts to Hebei to promote technological progress.
</P>
<P>
They have helped their partners in poor areas to dig 1,905
wells, build 121 pump stations to increase the irrigated
area by 60,660 hectares, bring electricity to 360 villages by
putting up 300-kilometer-long power-transmission lines and open
3,600 training courses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Seek New Ways of Embalming Ancient Corpse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
successfully used a new biological plastination process to
preserve an ancient corpse of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644),
keeping the body for three months at normal room temperature.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said it is a major breakthrough in embalming
ancient corpses. It is the first time in the world that an ancient
corpse has been treated this way, they claimed.
</P>
<P>
The process involves immersing the body in epoxy resin and
polymers for at least one week following antiseptic injection. The
body is placed on a special wooden bed for hardening.
</P>
<P>
The Ming Dynasty corpse was unearthed in Dongguan, a city in
South China's Guangdong Province, at the beginning of last
year. Cooperating with the Dongguang Museum, the Guangdong College
of Pharmacy used the biological plastination process after 10
months.
</P>
<P>
After plastination, the body has kept its original shape, color
and elasticity just as it was after being unearthed. The preserved
corpse is on exhibit in the Dongguan Museum.
</P>
<P>
In the past, unearthed ancient corpses were kept in a
formaldehyde solution or in a half dry-half wet manner. The
ancient bodies would become dry, deformed and change color over
time.
</P>
<P>
The new method is considered better than the formaldehyde
treatment as the plasticized corpses do not have a bad odor, are
non-toxic and cannot easily be damaged.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong College of Pharmacy introduced the technology from
abroad and has established a biological plastination lab. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Scientists Develop Silage from Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan scientists have
successfully developed silage from water hyacinth, The New Vision
reported today.
</P>
<P>
David Mutetikka, a senior animal science lecturer in the
faculty of agriculture in Makerere University in Kampala, said he
had made the silage from four doses of water hyacinth mixed with
one dose of maize bran kept in air-tight polythene bags for three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Maize bran is the best additive the scientists tried, and can
give the silage the best flavor and form, and the cattle like
the mixed silage, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The mixed silage can be stored for several years and can be
used as a buffer feed for cattles, the scientist said.
</P>
<P>
The spell of long drought has caused death of cattles in this
country due to lack of grass to feed them.
</P>
<P>
But Mutetikka added that they are still testing the silage.
</P>
<P>
"The next step is to find out how well the animals grow when
fed on this mixture," he told the paper.
</P>
<P>
Water hyacinth covers 6,000 hectares of Lake Victoria and has
posed as an environmental pollution in the region. People
collected the weed and dumped it as rubbish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
