<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 34,000 Prisoners Escape in S. Africa in Last Four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A police survey has shown
that more than 34,000 prisoners in South Africa have escaped from
custody in the past four years, local daily the Citizen reported
today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 34,128 awaiting-trial prisoners have escaped
countrywide since 1994 when the first non-racial general
elections were held, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Leon Engelbrecht, a senior police official in South Africa's
Crime Prevention Division, said the escapes mainly were results
of negligence on the part of police officers.
</P>
<P>
Last year 888 police officers were prosecuted departmentally
in this regard, which was an increase of 30 percent over the
previous year while 171 officers were criminally prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Police commissioners in South African provinces late in
December submitted contingency plans to curb escapes in their
areas and it was decided, among other things, that standing
regulations pertaining to prisoners should be adhered to more
strictly.
</P>
<P>
The provincial plans are in the process of being evaluated
with a view to drawing up national orders for the prevention of
escapes from police custody. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi, Pakistani Leaders Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Friday held
formal talks in Dhaka on bilateral relations and other issues of
common concern.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two prime ministers expressed their hope
that bilateral economic and trade relations would further develop
in the future, Bangladeshi Foreign Secretary Nostafizur Rahman
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the two sides signed a five-year agreement on
cultural cooperation between the two South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Sharif arrived here Thursday morning to attend the
Bangladesh-India-Pakistan business summit held in Dhaka Thursday
afternoon, and for a two-day official visit to Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
He will take a boat trip to south Bangladesh's Sundarbans, the
largest mangrove forest in the world, on Saturday morning before
leaving for Islamabad in the afternoon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
