<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Eases Ban on Fish Imports From East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
relaxed the ban on fish imports from Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania and
Mozambique, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Products from fish caught, frozen and packed in their final
packaging off the coast of the above countries and exported
directly to the EU are now exempted from the embargo, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, frozen or processed fish products from the three east
African countries and Mozambique will be subjected to a
microbiological examination "to verify that they pose no threat
to public health," said an EU statement issued here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The examination shall be carried out, in particular, to
detect the presence of salmonellae," said the statement, adding
that sterilized fish products are exempted from the test.
</P>
<P>
The EU introduced the sanction of importation of fish and fish
products from the four nations on December 23, 1997 as a result
of a cholera outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Medical and Fisheries Department officials in Kenya criticized
the move, saying it was unjustified.
</P>
<P>
The cholera outbreak owing to heavy rains caused by the El
Nino weather phenomenon, has claimed over 1,000 lives since
November in Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Disaster Victims Cherish Hope (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A blanket of snow has
covered structures destroyed in the devastating January 10
earthquake which hit Zhangbei and Shangyi Counties of north
China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Some 500,000 victims living in affected areas covering over
2,000 sq.km. find it difficult to face unfamiliar surroundings of
collapsed houses, buried grain and damaged belongings. Nonetheless
they sincerely hope the snow will provide them with sustenance and
bring vitality to surrounding farmland.
</P>
<P>
In one case, Xing Zhao and his mother, villagers in Xingjialiang
Village, Zhangbei County, near the epicenter, stood silently in
front of their destroyed courtyard staring at the ruins of what
was once their new house.
</P>
<P>
Xing, 25, spent two years building the house in time for his
wedding. The young man picked up pieces of broken tile and bricks
and pledged, "I'll rebuild the house when it gets warmer."
</P>
<P>
The quake, which measured 6.2 on the Richter Scale, and
frequent aftershocks over the past six days have killed about 50
people, left over 12,000 people injured, and destroyed or damaged
well over 200,000 houses.
</P>
<P>
Many of the victims in the affected areas are living in tents
equipped with stoves. Smiles on the faces of villagers living in
the new tent compounds hint that they have regained hope and
courage for rebuilding their homes and villages.
</P>
<P>
Twenty soliders from the People's Liberation Army (PLA) are
busy erecting new tents for villagers from Xingjialiang Village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Disaster Victims Cherish Hope (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The soliders, who arrived in the village on the day of the
quake, donated their personal quilts and coats to quake
victims. Three soldiers now share one quilt.
</P>
<P>
One officer named Xu Xinyin rubbed his hands to keep warm and
commented: "We've spent the last two days trying to move all
villagers to warm tents with cooking equipment."
</P>
<P>
PLA soliders, 17 medical teams and rescue teams have continued
to work despite new difficulties created by heavy snow.
</P>
<P>
"We will most likely spend Spring Festival (which will fall on
January 28 this year) here, and my colleagues are prepared to stay
even longer," according to Liu Minghua, a PLA medical officer.
</P>
<P>
Liu's medical team, consisting of 26 doctors and nurses, has
treated 3,005 injured villagers in Dahe Township over the past few
days alone.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles carrying relief supplies from nearby cities are a
common site along highways leading to quake-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Statistics covering the period through Thursday show that
affected areas have received donations of over 10 million yuan,
120,000 coats and more than 70,000 quilts, as well as 20,000 boxes
of instant food products and pharmaceuticals valued at 200,000
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Relief aid from throughout the nation will enable local
residents to bear the burdens of even more difficulties arising
from frigid temperatures forecast for the coming days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
