<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Sports Officials Condemn Doping Offences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Top officials of the Chinese
Olympic Committee (COC) strongly condemned the ugly doping
offences in a two-hour meeting here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
COC President Wu Shaozu, also Minister of the Chinese State
Physical Culture and Sports Commission, said that the several
Chinese doping offenders had smeared the reputation of the Chinese
sports.
</P>
<P>
The International Swimming Federation announced on January 11
four Chinese swimmers were tested positive in their A samples in
an out-of-competition test at the World Swimming Championships in
Perth, Australia, and a swimmer and her coach were caught of
trafficking in banned substances by the Sydney Customs on January
8.
</P>
<P>
"The cases during the championships dealt a heavy blow to the
Chinese sports. I feel heart broken about this," he said. "Some
persons did not join in the fight against doping seriously, but
tried to exploit the regulations."
</P>
<P>
It was announced at the meeting that a five-member special
panel has been set up to carry out its serious and thorough
investigation into the cases.
</P>
<P>
The panel includes COC vice president, director of the COC
Supervision Office, an anti-doping expert and official as well as
a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
COC Vice-President Yuan Weimin said at the meeting that COC
will continue to tackle such doping offences comprehensively by
combining efforts through legislative, adminstrative, technical
and economic measures and to ensure its anti-doping momentum and
effectiveness with special anti-doping offices to be set up in the
provincial level.
</P>
<P>
"Some persons only take an anti-doping token campaign and
became the victims of honors and incentives such as administrative
posts, priviliges, housing and money," Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
"We will not only make our unremitting efforts to fight against
doping, but also reject biased attacks by a few sports officials
with double standards," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yang Tianle, an anti-doping Chinese expert, warned those who
take the risk to break the rules will eventually do harm to
themselves and distort the image of the country.
</P>
<P>
"As the technology advances, even the most shrewd users of the
banned substance will be caught up for sure," Yang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
