<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Economist Makes Predictions for '98 Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China, thanks to its huge
surplus in trade and a foreign exchange reserve of more than 100
billion U.S. dollars, would be able to weather economic turmoil
unlike other Asian nations, said Kazuo Nakamura, chief economist
of Japan's Daiichi Kangyo Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, China would also slow down a bit owing to the
depression in Asia which would force the whole world to enter a
period of economic adjustment, Kazuo said.
</P>
<P>
Kazuo made his predictions here today in an economy and finance
report jointly organized by China's Five Best Economic Consulting
Companies and the Daiichi Kangyo Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the world's economy will grow only 3
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
After looking back to the global economy and finances in 1997,
he said the limited pace of the Asian economy and a slower
increase in the United States and other countries would slow the
speed of world economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the actual growth rate of the global economy
this year would fall 0.9 percentage to 3 percent from last year's
3.9 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth rate of some Asian countries will slump
this year, he predicted, saying that Thailand would have a second
year of declining economic growth while the Republic of Korea
(ROK) would stay at the 1996 levels.
</P>
<P>
However, he said these countries have already endured high
inflation, and would restore exports and reduce imports. As a
result, the slump should hit bottom by the second half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
He also forecast economic growth by the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations at around 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Japan's economy fell by 0.2 percent last year, he said, and
predicted it would drop even lower if no good policy was put
forward.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0236 </DOCNO>
