<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Reforms Fail to Impress Currency, Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- New reform measures announced
by the Indonesian government Thursday failed to impress the
financial markets, with both the rupiah, the national currency,
and share prices losing ground in moderate trading.
</P>
<P>
"The price of the rupiah in the market has been discounted by
the high expectation of the market on the visit of IMF
(International Monetary Fund) officials to Indonesia," local press
Friday quoted a currency dealer as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government announced Thursday transparent and concrete
economic measures including a more realistic review of the 1998/99
state budget proposed to curtail government financial support for
a national car project and scrap some agricultural monopolies.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah strengthened to as high as 6,950 against the U.S.
dollar shortly after President Soeharto announced the economic
reforms, but it failed to maintain its extended three-day gains
and fell to as low as 8,450 to the dollar in the afternoon on a
combination of high dollar demand by local corporations.
</P>
<P>
The spot rupiah closed at 8,450/8,700 after crossing the 8,000
psychological level against an opening of 7,200/7,400 in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
"But (the) volume remains thin with very limited transactions,"
a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
"It's just a pity that good news on economic reforms announced
by the government failed to put the rupiah on an upward trend,
because (U.S.) Standard and Poor's announced the downgrade rating
of Indonesian banks," another dealer said.
</P>
<P>
As the rupiah fell, stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange
also descended after a three-day rally on profit taking, with the
main price index falling 13.74 points to close at 387.243 from
403.98 the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Stock brokers attributed the fall of stock prices to profit
taking by most investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Opens Domestic Market Wider to Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The annual growth rate in
introducing overseas funds by south China's Guangdong Province
exceeded 23.6 percent during the 1993-1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, adjacent to Hong Kong and Macao and a financial
center for Southeast Asia, actually used 13.9 billion U.S. dollars
of overseas funds in 1997, said Lu Ruihua, provincial governor.
</P>
<P>
Lu said the rapid growth in overseas investment and exports is
the key force driving the province's economy.
</P>
<P>
The imports and exports of the province have accounted for 40
percent of the country's total. And the annual growth rate of
foreign trade has reached 14.1 percent during the past five years,
according to Lu.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the province earned 127 billion U.S. dollars in foreign
trade. The exports totaled 72 billion U.S. dollars, up 21.3
percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Lu pointed out that the province should introduce more advanced
technologies, key equipment and raw materials in which China is
deficient, while exporting products with high added value and
technological content.
</P>
<P>
The province, the ancestral home of approximately 20 million
overseas Chinese, should create more efficient access to recruit
overseas investment, especially large trans-national companies, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Lu said the priority for absorbing overseas funds should be
given to highly efficient agriculture, basic industries,
infrastructure construction and high-tech projects.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the province should provide a healthy
environment and favorable conditions for the promotion of economic
and technological cooperation with Hong Kong and Macao, and seek
common development and prosperity with the two regions in line
with policies of the Chinese central government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
