<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Make Kenya's Maize Yield Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Last season's maize production
around Kenya is expected to drop by nearly 20 percent, largely
due to mounting post-harvest losses caused by continuous heavy
rains, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Famine Early Warning System section of USAID
and the Regional Economic Development Services Office says the
nationwide long rains maize output is expected to drop from a
1991-96 average of 2.22 million tons to 1.83 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The worst-hit area is Kenya's Rift Valley Province, the
national breadbasket, where production will drop by a third, from
an average of 1.25 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The report says harvesting of the season's maize crop has
neared completion with a significant decline in output due to
"increased post-harvest losses as a result of high moisture
content of harvested grains, amidst inadequate on-farm storage
capacity."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it predicts a temporary decline in prices in the
short-rains producing areas during the February peak harvesting
period.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, production of beans in Eastern
Province is "expected to decline by up to 30 percent" in the
current short rains season.
</P>
<P>
Excessive rainfall in the Lake Victoria basin has resulted in
major rivers bursting their banks, "destroying 650 hectares of
crops and submerging 3,000 hectares of land and displacing up to
2,000 families," the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
