<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Attains Self-Sufficiency in Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 16 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province, one of the country's most developed areas, harvested 19
million tons of grain in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that it was the first time for the province to
have good grain harvests for consecutive four years.
</P>
<P>
The per capita farmland of the province is only equal to half
the national average, but its economic growth rate of 10.6 percent
in 1997 was 1.8 percent higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The province has reached self-sufficiency in grain because of
efforts made by the local government, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government would allocate 50 million yuan (6.25
million U.S. dollars) to explore farmlands every year since 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the province has paid close attention to the
use of agro-sciences and reclaiming farmland, which are the key
forces driving its agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The advanced rice-seedling-throwing technique has been used on
930,000 hectares of farmland. The province has improved more than
130,000 hectares of low-yield farmland in the last three years,
with a combined investment of more than 5 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
