<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cultural Relics To Be Show in U.S. Modern Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 16 (Xinhua) -- American people will have a
chance to watch creams of Chinese cultural relics without the
trouble of coming to China.
</P>
<P>
It is learned here today that New York-based Guggenheim Museum,
which is famous for its modern architectural style and modern art
collection, will play host to an exhibition on Chinese cultural
relics next month.
</P>
<P>
The four-month exhibition starting from early February, will be
sponsored by China Cultural Relics Exchange Center. The exhibition
is expected to outline the 5,000-year civilization of China.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent of the 250 items of exhibits are
first-grade rare relics of the country, much higher than previous
exhibitions overseas.
</P>
<P>
Included in the exhibition are some 30 modern paintings and 218
items of historical relics such as painted pottery, bronze, jade,
gold and silver, lacquer, stone sculptures, silk and traditional
Chinese paintings.
</P>
<P>
The relics, dating from as early as the late Stone Age to the
late Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), are mostly creams of those
unearthed in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
Some of exhibits represented the top level of their kind in
ancient China, such as a neolithic pottery basin with the design
of a human face combined with a fish, a jade sacrificial article,
a bronze mask with protruding eyes, and silk of the Han Dynasty
(206 BC-220 AD) found in a prince's tomb.
</P>
<P>
Experts value a "mi se" (mysterious color) porcelain vase from
the Tang Dynasty (618-907) found in the underground palace of a
temple in northwest China's Shaanxi Province. Yet the visitors
might be more interested in terracotta warriors serving as nether
world guards of Qin Shi Huang, the first emperor of China who set
up the Qin Dynasty 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Also attractive might be a stone sculpture of a Buddha, which,
though headless, has a beautiful figure in exquisite clothes and
decorations.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the sculpture is regarded as "Oriental Venus."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Help China Reform Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is willing to
provide the techniques and funds necessary for China's
pension insurance reform, a bank official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yukon Huang, director of the World Bank in China, made this
pledge during a three-day seminar on the old-age insurance reform
and funds management.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 financial experts and officials from at home and
abroad attended the seminar, which was held in Yangzhou city, east
China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Huang predicted that China will soon become a gerontological
society, with declining birth rates and longer life spans. China
will have 300 million elderly by 2015.
</P>
<P>
China began setting up a large-scale old-age insurance system
in 1986. By the end of 1996, 87 million employees had joined
various pension plans and 23 million retired workers had received
money from the plans.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that expanding the country's pension funds will have
a major impact on the capital market in China and the world. By 2030
China's old-age insurance funds are expected to reach nearly 1.8
trillion U.S. dollars by 2030.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank has cooperated with the country on
research and held information seminars.
</P>
<P>
China has decided to establish a unified pension insurance
system by the end of the century to replace the current flexible
pilot program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
