<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Flood Parts of Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A sixteen hour non-stop
downpour, blamed on the El Nino phenomenon, Thursday flooded
Nairobi's already collapsing roads and submerged houses in some
middle-class neighborhoods and shacks in teeming shantytowns.
</P>
<P>
More rains are expected today, said weather experts, adding
that Thursday's rains, recorded at 107 mm, were the heaviest
experienced by Nairobi in current season, with southern and
eastern districts suffering the highest rainfall level.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of city residents failed to report to work and were
kept at home by the rains while huge queues of cars, trucks and
commuter buses struggled through pools of water on main roads to
the city, many having to dodge vehicles stalled in the deluge.
</P>
<P>
"I have lived here for more than 10 years and can tell you
I've never seen anything like this," said businessman Onesmus
Gathoga, surveying his submerged new house in Nairobi's Eastleigh
suburb.
</P>
<P>
In a middle-class estate in Nairobi's South B, teenagers
formed emergency water transport gangs, ferrying residents on
their backs or in makeshift plastic canoes.
</P>
<P>
Children unaware of potential health hazards splashed in pools
of water next to a rubbish tip. The rains have added to a
deteriorating sanitary situation in Nairobi, once rated one of
Africa's best-kept cities.
</P>
<P>
Last November, when the El Nino rains first hit Kenya and
wreaked havoc in Coast and North Eastern provinces, Nairobi was
spared.
</P>
<P>
With many bridges washed away and landslides blocking roads in
far-flung parts of the country, economists have warned the
authorities of a threat to economic growth and a major headache
for an already tight state budget.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi said Thursday the government was
starting emergency food distribution to all areas under floods.
</P>
<P>
This year's long rains season, which should start in Kenya
late March, may also be replaced by a spell of drought, the
experts predicted earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Global forecast indicated that the El Nino weather phenomenon
has been on a downward trend from December and was likely to end
in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
