<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Ends Mandate in Eastern Slavonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, January 15 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Transitional
Administration for Eastern Slavonia, Baranja and West Sirmium
(UNTAES) formally transferred its powers to the Croatian
authorities Thursday after two years of administration over the
three territories.
</P>
<P>
A handover ceremony was held in Vukovar, capital of Eastern
Slavonia.
</P>
<P>
According to the No.1023 U.N. Resolution passed by the U.N.
Security Council, the mandate of UNTAES and international armed
forces expires on January 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Attending a celebration here tonight, President Franjo Tudjman
expressed his great delight over Croatia's exercise of sovereignty
over its entire territory.
</P>
<P>
He said the handover marked the beginning of a new era for his
country, which would be able to concentrate on economic and
cultural development and international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Other Croatian officials attending the ceremony in Vukovar
hoped the refugees from the region could quickly return home after
the handover.
</P>
<P>
They also hoped the international community could extend
financial support to help the refugees rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
Following the disintegration of the former Yugoslavia, the
Serbs, who were the majority of the habitants in the three
regions, sought independence and ran into armed conflicts with the
Croatian authorities.
</P>
<P>
To prevent a potential civil war, the U.N. Security Council
adopted a series of resolutions on administrative intervention and
established UNTAES to ensure a gradual and peaceful transfer of
the local authorities to the Croatian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
