<HEADLINE> China Making Progress in Mineral Prospecting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists discovered
151 mineral deposits, 18 gas wells and 185 million tons of mineral
nodules containing manganese, cobalt, copper, nickel and other
elements in 1997, the overseas edition of People's Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Geologists also have found fresh drinking water in Tarim Basin,
Hexi Corridor, loess plateau and other places.
</P>
<P>
Large gold, silver and copper mines have been discovered in
southwest China's Sichuan and Yunnan provinces.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources earned
34.63 million U.S. dollars by exporting mineral products, up 77
percent from the previous year's figure.
</P>
<P>
The country used 11.44 million U.S. dollars of foreign funds in
tapping more than 20 gold and diamond deposits last year.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen geological teams in Shaanxi, Jiangsu and Zhejiang
provinces are prospecting for mineral resources in 13
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
