<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Residents Have High Sense of Wild Animal Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Residents in north China's
Tianjin Municipality have shown a high sense of protecting wild
animals.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, the number of wild animals donated by local
residents reached 32 in 14 species, with eight rare animals under
state protection. These animals include cinereous vulture and
white heron.
</P>
<P>
One day, Zhao Guoxiang, manager of a flower company, found a
goose being auctioned. He spent 500 yuan to buy the goose and
presented it to the Tianjin Zoo.
</P>
<P>
The zoo has opened a special telephone to provide convenience
for donators, in a bid to save endangered animals. 
</P>
