<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Working to Create Jobs for Factory Laid-offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will speed up the pace
in pushing re-employment projects involving laid-off workers,
according to the municipal bureau of labor.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing Evening News" reported that according to the bureau's
policies on re-employment, laid-offs who are younger than 35 years
old are encouraged to find jobs by themselves; those who are
between 35-45 years old can find jobs through the labor market and
technical training.
</P>
<P>
State enterprises are encouraged to develop diversified
businesses based on their existing equipment and technologies to
create more jobs for their own workers; laid-off workers and
people who are waiting for jobs are also encouraged to set
stock-holding joint ventures and other economic entities with
their funds, technologies and labor skills.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the total number of the city's laid-off
workers will reach 190,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1997, 137,000 out of the city's 170,000
laid-offs found new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
