<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Battles Illegal Cigarette Smuggling and Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China has launched a massive
battle to crack down on the smuggling and production of poor
quality and counterfeit cigarettes to defend the tobacco monopoly.
</P>
<P>
China uncovered and confiscated 2.3 billion cartons, cases or
packages of smuggled cigarettes in 1997 and destroyed 684 illegal
production sites using counterfeit trademarks, according to Zhou
Ruizeng, a senior official with the State Tobacco Monopoly
Administration (STMA).
</P>
<P>
The extensive effort included the confiscation of 2,400 pieces of
equipment used to produce counterfeit cigarettes and 4.7 billion
packages of cigarettes bearing counterfeit trademarks,
as well as the closure of 79 illegal cigarette wholesale markets.
</P>
<P>
Zhou noted that China reduced cigarette production in 1997, but
nonetheless filled State coffers with record profits and taxes of
90 billion yuan, up 8.4 percent on the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Non-Ferrous Metals Industry Overcoming Difficulties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Faced with both declining
product prices and cost hikes in 1997, China's non-ferrous metals
industry was still able to increase its efficiency based on
economies of scale and lower production costs.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang Guang, assistant to the general manager of
the China National Nonferrous Metals Industry Corp. (CNNC), they
saved 1.1 billion yuan of energy in 1997 as well as 107 million
yuan in administration expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The industry's deficit was reduced substantially after CNNC's
restructuring and personnel cutbacks. After May, financially
troubled enterprises under CNNC reduced their losses on a monthly
basis and profitable ones increased their earnings.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is expecting a full year's profit of 100
million yuan for 1997 when statistical information is completed.
</P>
<P>
Last year was the first of three during which CNNC will be
transformed into a joint-stock company with the state holding
majority interest, according to China Metals, an industry
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 16 more CNNC enterprises began the transformation into
modern companies, bringing the number of such enterprises to
27. The 27 enterprises own two-thirds of all state assets in the
corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Non-Ferrous Metals Industry Overcoming Difficulties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Twelve CNNC mergers and so-called "personnel-reduction-and
efficiency-enhancement" (PREE) cases have been approved by the
State Office on Enterprises Merger, Bankruptcy, PREE and
Re-employment Program, China Metals reported. The enterprises
involved in the program have been exempted from a combined
interest payment of 430 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade of non-ferrous metals made progress in 1997. The
total trade volume is estimated at 1.8 billion U.S. dollars,
including exports totalling 1.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The corporation won 18 overseas engineering contracts worth 500
million U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
CNNC has also begun to unify exports and imports of staple
commodities. In 1997, it imported 483,500 tons of copper
concentrates and 404,000 tons of alumina oxide, and exported
325,000 tons of zinc ingots.
</P>
<P>
The non-ferrous metals industry maintained growth for the 15th
year. Its total production remained the world's largest next to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to CNNC estimates, production of the 10 major metals
-- copper, aluminum, lead, zinc, nickel, tin, magnesium, antimony,
mercury and titanium -- reached 5.3 million tons, up 1.33 percent
over 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, by type of metal, copper production is estimated at
1.05 million tons, up 15.38 percent; aluminium, 2.05 million tons,
up 15.17 percent; zinc, 1.35 million tons, up 20.54 percent; and
lead, 600,000 tons, down 15.03 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
