<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Encouraged to Hold Stocks in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan Province in southwest
China is taking steps to encourage workers to buy into their
enterprises as one form to bring the poorly-operating state
sector out of difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The Jijie Smeltery in Gejiu city is one of the examples. It was
transformed into a stock company last November, registering 20
million yuan worth of 20 million shares. Workers of the factory
bought 85 percent of the stocks, while the state kept only 10
percent, with the remainder going to society at large.
</P>
<P>
The smeltery is one of China's major wolfram enterprises, with
its lead and zinc production ranking 11th in the country, but its
asset-liability ratio was as high as 90 percent. It has 2,500
workers and staff members, as well as 450 retired workers.
</P>
<P>
The reform was designed to link up workers financially with
enterprises in the form of capital, and to promote workers to help
run their businesses, according to local economic departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
