<HEADLINE> China-Kazakhstan Relations Expected to Move Forward: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh Ambassador to China
Kuanysh Sultanov told a news conference Thursday that he is
confident of further development of China-Kazakhstan relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries yielded successful results in
bilateral cooperation in 1997. Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev paid a state visit to China early last year, during
which the two sides formulated a plan for bilateral cooperation
for the whole year, including oil and transportation cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Nazarbayev's visit to China, the two countries also
attended a five-country summit held in Moscow in April of 1997 and
signed a military agreement, establishing a relationship of mutual
trust in the military field, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier Li Lanqing visited
Kazakhstan in September of 1997, when the two countries signed an
oil agreement valued at 9.5 billion U.S. dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador pointed out that bilateral relations will
continue to grow in the new year through the implementation of the
oil agreement and the visit to China by the head of the Kazakh
government.
</P>
<P>
He said Kazakhstan is expected to hold a symposium in the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region to attract investment.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Chinese language has become more popular
in Kazakhstan thanks to the development of bilateral relations in
recent years. Many colleges and middle schools in the country now
offer language training in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the China International Trade Center is
also under way in Akmola, the new capital city of Kazakhstan,
according to the ambassador.  
</P>
</TEXT>
