<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Want Shia Scholars Out of Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A peaceful resolution of the
Afghan imbroglio seems elusive again after the Islamic Taliban
militia declined to accept Islamic scholars from the rival
northern alliance for proposed peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's supreme leader Mohammad Umar has announced that
only those opposition Ulema of the Muslim religion, who had passed
out from the recognized institutions, would be acceptable for
discussions, according to a report carried by a major local
newspaper The Muslim on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued from Kandahar, a major city in southern
Afghanistan, Umar said the Taliban will not succumb to any
pressures for a broad-based government in Kabul as it would
further complicate the problem, the paper said. However, it did
not mention when Umar issued the statement.
</P>
<P>
Umar said those Ulema holding degrees of international repute
would be invited to the commission as agreed after the shuttle
diplomacy of Pakistan in a bid to bring all the major warring
factions of Afghanistan to the negotiating table, The Muslim said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some of the opposition parties have also threatened
not to join the proposed commission if the Taliban fail to
entertain scholars from the north, particularly those belonging to
Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to Afghan sources, the convening of a joint meeting
of Ulema from the Taliban and the northern alliance seems to be
unlikely at present as the Taliban leaders are hardly prepared to
accommodate Ulema of the Shia, who dominate the anti-Taliban
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban now control two-thirds of Afghanistan including the
capital of Kabul while the northern alliance holds the remaining
one-third.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
