<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "China Will Continue to Open Financial Sector to Outside" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Financial turbulences in
Southeast Asian countries will not affect the implementation of
China's policy to open its financial sector to the outside world,
Dai Xianglong, central bank governor, said here today.
</P>
<P>
To this end, China is expected to give approval to more
overseas banks and insurance companies to set up branches in the
country this year, and more overseas bank branches will be given
the license to handle the RMB yuan business, Dai said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
"But we will impose stricter control over the applicant's
qualifications and the operations of such institutions," according
to the central bank governor.
</P>
<P>
And China will draw lessons from the financial volatility in
Southeast Asia and will take a more cautious approach to realizing
the convertibility of the RMB yuan under the capital account, Dai
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The operational branches of overseas financial institutions in
China already reached 166 last year, with the combined assets
estimated at 30.64 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
