<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Flights to, From Bangkok Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Several international airlines
have in the past few months reduced or requested to reduce their
flights to and from Bangkok as the economic crisis in Asia has
affected their profitability.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has urged the Thai people to tour their own
country rather than spend their holidays aboard and Thais must
produce air tickets and visas if they want to get foreign
currencies for their overseas trips.
</P>
<P>
Passenger numbers on Asia routes have fallen 50-70 percent
because of the economic downturn in the region and Indonesia's
thick smog, according to the Nation newspaper on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Airways International (THAI), the Thai national
flag-carrier, plans to cut its Bangkok-Seoul flights from 25 a
week to 21, and Bangkok-Ho Chi Minh City from 15 to 13 a week.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Asiana has slashed its Seoul-Bangkok operations
from nine flights to eight a week while Air Macau has reduced its
Macau-Bangkok flights from four to three a week.
</P>
<P>
France's Cors Air has cut down its Paris-Bangkok flights from
two to one each week and the Germany-based Lufthansa Airlines has
announced plans to reduce its operations between Germany and
Thailand from 13 flights to 10 a week, effective from late March,
for the summer season.
</P>
<P>
From late February Australia's Qantas is to suspend its three
weekly services between Brisbane and Bangkok and its twice weekly
non-stop service between Perth and Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The slump in Asia's outbound tourism has forced airlines
managers to reconsider their pricing strategies and revise route
destinations to survive fiercer competition among airlines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian MPs May Hold Concurrent Posts in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The Mongolian State Great
Hural (Parliament) members regained the possibility of holding
concurrent posts in the government after an amendment was adopted
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Great Hural said the amendment was adopted to strengthen
its supervision in the government and prevent rivalries.
</P>
<P>
As a parliamentary country, the Mongolian government should be
appointed by the Great Hural.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Great Hural were allowed to be a government
minister two years ago but were forbidden from July of 1996 after
the Democratic Union won the parliament elections.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the adoption of the amendments opened the
way for a government reshuffle in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
