<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's Trade Increases in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The total trade volume of
Yugoslavia reached 7.167 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, up 20.8
percent from 1996, the Yugoslav news agency, Tanjug, reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Milovan Zivkovic, chairman of the Yugoslav Statistics Bureau,
said the export volume of the country reached 2.368 billion
dollars in 1997, an increase of 28.6 over 1996. Imports increased
by 17 percent, amounting to 4.799 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has more than 100 trade partner countries, and.
exports to the European Union market accounted for 85 percent of
the total export volume.
</P>
<P>
The biggest trade partner on the import side was Italy which
took 272 million dollars worth of goods from Yugoslavia, while the
biggest exporter was Germany which sold 730 million dollars worth
of goods to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Zivkovic said Yugoslavia's imports of materials were mainly for
making goods which could be exported. That was why the country had
a trade deficit of 2.4 billion dollars in 1997, he added.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia would reduce this deficit step-by-step in the
future, Zivkovic said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
