<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Slip Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Uncertainty generated by the
Asian currency crisis continued to drive wool prices down at sales
in the two Australian cities of Sydney and Geelong this week.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator fell 10 Australian cents to finish
at 673 cents a clean kilogram, bordering on its lowest level for
this season, the Australian Council of Wool Exporters said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The western market indicator remained unchanged at 633 cents
per kilogram as there were no sales in Fremantle city.
</P>
<P>
A total of 60,621 bales were offered.
</P>
<P>
"Although wool remains relatively cheap in terms of U.S.
dollars, and with respect to some of the major European
currencies, there is not much confidence in the buying and
exporting trade at present as most people expect that it will take
a considerable time for stability to return to both Asian and
global markets following developments of the last six months," the
council said.
</P>
<P>
"It is also not clear whether the fallout seen in (South) Korea
will flow on to other major Asian wool consuming markets such as
Japan and China."
</P>
<P>
Little business has been written since early November as Korean
wool importers, mills and banks have been hit by severe liquidity
problems.
</P>
<P>
"Similarly, most exporters to China are anxiously awaiting the
opening of many overdue letters of credit," it said.
</P>
<P>
About 83,300 bales are rostered for sales in Sydney, Melbourne
and Fremantle next week.
</P>
<P>
Wesfarmers Dalgety is more optimistic in its weekly wool
report, noting the fall was not as severe as last week.
</P>
<P>
"Many buyers have adopted a wait and see attitude in the
current uncertain environment created by the Asian economic
downturn and the sharp drop in wool prices last sale," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"In the medium term, the Asian economic situation looks set to
continue to have a negative effect on wool prices, although the
extent of this is still uncertain," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
