<HEADLINE> Malaysian, IMF Officials Discuss Regional Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad met here Friday with International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Managing Director Michel Camdessus to discuss the current
economic problems facing several Asian countries, including
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief praised Malaysia for the measures taken to
overcome its economic problem. The measures include scaling down
economic growth from 7 percent to between 4 and 5 percent,
deferring large projects, cutting government expenditure by 18
percent, curbing credit growth and ensuring loans for productive
sectors only.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said he appreciated and welcomed the austerity
measures adopted by Malaysia as announced by its Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim on December 5 last
year.
</P>
<P>
"I told the prime minister my appreciation for the adoption of
the measures ... it was timely adopted," Camdessus told reporters
after the talks here.
</P>
<P>
"We have commented about the prospective of this country
(Malaysia) and the way in helping it recover from the present
downturn and strengthen it enough to enable it to have a
sustainable growth to achieve the ambition Prime Minister Mahathir
has for his country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief hoped that Malaysia could weather its economic
crisis on its own without having to resort to major international
support.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has said that it has no intention of seeking IMF
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Soon after his arrival here Thursday evening, Camdessus
discussed with Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar
Ibrahim the attack on regional currencies and the policies adopted
by countries affected by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus is visiting a number of Asian countries in an effort
to mitigate the economic crisis facing the region.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, who flew in from Indonesia Thursday for a two-day
visit, will leave for Singapore later Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
