<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Australians Return From South Pole Walk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The first three Australians to
walk to the South Pole without support returned to Sydney Friday.
</P>
<P>
Peter Treseder, Ian Brown and Keith Williams, all in their 40s,
described their epic 60-day trek as exhausting but exhilarating,
the Australian Associated press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Apart from deadened skin on their noses, fingernails blackened
by frostbite and full-faced beards, they showed few visible signs
of their epic feat.
</P>
<P>
They left Sydney on October 20 last year, reached Berkner
Island, Antarctica, on November 3 and arrived at the pole on New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
Treseder, who led the expedition, said the toughest part had
been its totality.
</P>
<P>
"There's nothing to break the monotony, there's no bird life,
no animal life and you get up every morning out of your tent ...
and it looks exactly the same," he told journalists at Sydney
airport.
</P>
<P>
"It's almost like a giant treadmill ... and it's so big you can
see the curvature of the earth as you look right around the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
"Just endless, endless white and nothing to stop the katabatic
winds that ... bombard you all day."
</P>
<P>
He said the success of the campaign had been seriously
jeopardized only once, when Brown's inner thighs had become so
severely frostbitten he was reluctant to go on.
</P>
<P>
"There were moments when we had our doubts whether the team
would make it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Three packs of biscuits served as the staple diet for each of
them throughout their nine-hour daily trek, complemented by 6,000
calorie worth of dried milk, pasta, olive oil, soup, vitamin
supplements and chocolate to ward off minus 30 degree
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
Christmas Day included a feast of cashews and the luxury of
"climbing over each other to talk to our wives by radio."
</P>
<P>
Treseder celebrated his 40th birthday on November 11 and Brown
his 43rd a week later.
</P>
<P>
Williams, 40, said his biggest thrill had been crossing the
Trans-Antarctic Mountains.
</P>
<P>
"I'd been basically looking to see them (all my life) and it
was an emotional moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the terrain as a frozen seascape featuring
hundreds of kilometers of sastrugi, or chest-high ridges,
knee-deep snow and hard bare ice often laid over hidden glacial
crevasses.
</P>
<P>
Antarctica was not seen by human eyes until 1830.
</P>
<P>
The South Pole was first reached by Norwegian explorer Roald
Amundsen using dog teams in 1912, while the British "Footsteps of
Scott" Expedition became the first to walk there in 1986, AAP
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0284 </DOCNO>
