<HEADLINE> Mexico Reaffirms Commitment to Americas Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government on
Thursday reaffirmed is commitment to building the Free Trade Area
of the Americas (FTAA) by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario Green told a meeting preparing
for the coming Summit of Americas that free trade is a key
instrument in promoting economic development and increasing people's
living standards. The meeting is being held in Cancun, southeast
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
She said she is confident that April's Second Summit of the
Americas will agree on creating the FTAA by the year 2005. The
FTAA, to group Mexico, Canada, the United States and the Mercosur
members of Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay, was proposed
by U.S. President Bill Clinton at the 1994's Summit of the
Americas Conference in Miami.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has been keen in pushing ahead with the plan but Brazil
and Argentina remained lukewarm for fear that the U.S. blueprint
may overwhelm their own bloc.
</P>
<P>
The Second Summit of the Americas will be held on April 18 and
19 in Santiago, Chile. 
</P>
