<HEADLINE> Peso Crunch Takes Toll on Philippine Embassies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Department of
Foreign Affairs is recalling as many as 400 personnel assigned
abroad as part of its effort to cut expenses after the sharp
depreciation of the country's currency, the peso.
</P>
<P>
The 40-percent reduction in the staff of 80 embassies and
consulates all over the world is one of the ways the department is
using to cushion the blows of the currency turmoil, the local
daily Manila Standard reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon was quoted as saying Thursday
that the department has called on those assigned abroad to come
back in answer to voluntary recall.
</P>
<P>
Siazon hinted that this is not a good time to be assigned
abroad since the home office has already mandated a 30-percent
slash in all overseas allowances.
</P>
<P>
According to Siazon, the department will incur a deficit of 1.8
billion pesos if the peso is traded at 45 to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The peso recently dipped to a record low of 45 to the dollar
before slightly picking up to the 42 level Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The peso has so far lost nearly 60 percent of its value against
the dollar since its de facto devaluation in July 1997. Prior to
the devaluation, the peso-dollar exchange rate was at 26.4 pesos
to a dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
