<HEADLINE> China to Remain Attractive to Foreign Investors: Bank Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) - The governor of China's central
bank said today that the nation will overcome the effects of the
financial crisis in other Asian countries and continue to be an
ideal place for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
"I believe China will retain its position in 1998. China will
remain very attractive for foreign investment," Dai Xianglong,
governor of the People's Bank of China, said at a press conference
here this morning.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's second largest absorber of foreign
investment after the United States. Foreign direct investment
totaled 43 billion U.S. dollars in China last year.
</P>
<P>
Dai expected that the gross domestic product (GDP) will grow by
around eight percent this year, despite predictions that the Asian
crisis will affect China's exports.
</P>
<P>
"If we can put more vigorous efforts into opening up
international markets, then growth will be over eight percent," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He told that the national credit ceiling will hit 900 billion
yuan this year against 820 billion yuan in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
