<HEADLINE> Thai Canned Fruit Exporters Call for Easing Liquidity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports of canned
fruit and vegetables are expected to run into trouble this year if
the liquidity crunch and high interest rates are not eased, the
newspaper The Nation reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although a weakened baht has benefited agricultural exports,
continued lack of liquidity and high interest rates remain a
critical problem for exporters, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The lack of rainfall last year, attributed to the El Nino
phenomenon, could affect fruit and vegetable production and cause
difficulties to exporters of these products this year.
</P>
<P>
"If the liquidity crisis is not resolved as a matter of
priority, it will result in lower export growth this year,"
Phairoj Wangthamrongwit, managing director of Grand Asia Group, a
leading fruit and vegetable canner, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, some major importers of Thai products are
reluctant to place bulk orders for various reasons, such as their
own domestic economic downturn or the currency fluctuations, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Besides lower market demand, the liquidity problem has forced
exporters to cut prices to improve distribution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
