<HEADLINE> Thailand Speeds Up State Enterprises Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has put on
the fast track its plans to privatize state enterprises in the
energy, transport and infrastructure sectors, the local press
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Privatization is among the commitments the government made in
accepting a 17.2-billion-U.S.-dollar bailout package from the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
State enterprises, including the Airport Authority of Thailand
(AAT) and Second Bangkok International Airport Co. (SBIAC), have
been told to complete their privatization plans within one month.
</P>
<P>
The AAT has been asked to privatize the operations of its four
provincial airports at Phuket, Hat Yai, Chiang Mai and Chiang Rai
while  SBIAC has been called to sell more shares to private
investors to reduce government holdings.
</P>
<P>
Thai Airway International and Bangchak Petroleum will also be
required to divest more shares to private investors by June in
order to reduce the government's holdings to less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
