<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Readjust Interest Rates Timely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China will make fresh
readjustments to interest rates in line with changes in the
national economy this year, central bank governor Dai Xianglong
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Aggregate interest rates as well as their structure will be
timely and gradually adjusted," Dai told a press conference,
adding that one of the central bank's major tasks is to control
money supply appropriately through interest rate adjustments.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the central bank "does not intend to lower
interest rate at present".
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that monetary targets for 1998 include 16 to 18
percent increase in broad money, 17 percent increase in narrow
money and 14 percent increase in currency in circulation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy grew by 8.8 percent last year, with retail
price index climbing just one percent, leaving room for a further
interest rate cut following a reduction last October.
</P>
<P>
Dai forecasted that the Chinese economy will grow by more than
eight percent in 1998 while inflation will remain low.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the growth in retail price index will be well
under three percent this year, while the consumer price index is
expected to keep below five percent.
</P>
<P>
While reaffirming the central bank's "appropriately tight
monetary policy", Dai told that the overall scale of bank loans
will increase this year so as to ensure a proper economic growth.
</P>
<P>
More investment will be made to improve the agricultural
infrastructure and a housing oriented financial service system
will be developed to foster a housing market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dai told the press that the central bank has projected 100
billion yuan in loans to help foster a housing market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
