<HEADLINE> Dutch Defense Minister Decorated by Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian President Peter
Stoyanov Thursday conferred a decoration on Joris Voorhoeve, the
visiting Dutch defense minister, in recognition of his contribution
to the development of bilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The decoration was the Order of the Balkan Range, First Class,
the highest Bulgarian award to a foreigner who contributes to the
development of bilateral military relations.
</P>
<P>
Voorhoeve and his Bulgarian counterpart, Georgi Ananiev,
Wednesday signed an agreement on safeguarding classified military
information. It opens an opportunity for cooperation between the
two countries in the sensitive area of military intelligence
which, as Voorhoeve said, makes it very important.
</P>
<P>
The two defence ministers also discussed further cooperation
with the NATO-led multinational Stabilization Force (SFOR) in
Bosnia. They reached an understanding on the third group of
Bulgarian engineering troops which will relieve the Bulgarian
platoon currently committed to SFOR to undergo training in the
Netherlands in March.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral military cooperation is developing at high speed,
Voorhoeve told a joint news conference. He highly praised
Bulgaria's efforts to preserve stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Bulgaria, Voorhoeve also met Prime Minister
Ivan Kostov, Foreign Minister Nadezhda Mihailova, and the army's
chief of staff, Miho Mohov.
</P>
<P>
"Along with expanding our military cooperation we should also
expand our economic cooperation in order to secure the
Netherlands' support for our bid for NATO and European Union
membership," Ananiev told the news conference.
</P>
<P>
Voorhoeve, who headed a military delegation, ended his two-day
visit to Bulgaria Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
