<HEADLINE> Philippines to Import More Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
negotiating for the import of an additional 150,000 metric tons of
rice this year to boost the country's rice stock to prevent a rice
shortage, a senior food official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The extra amount will bring the total rice importation to
650,000 tons, of which some 500,000 tons were negotiated late last
year, National Food Authority Deputy Administrator Gregorio Tan
said.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are going on with Thailand, Vietnam and China on
the supply of the additional rice, Tan said, adding that the bulk
of rice imports this year are expected to come from Vietnam and
China.
</P>
<P>
Tan said the total 650,000-ton rice imports should arrive
before May just in time for the lean months.
</P>
<P>
During the first and second weeks of this month, a total of
74,500 tons of rice imports coming from Vietnam and China have
already arrived in the country.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the standby authority to import some 350,000
tons of corn has been frozen due to the high price of corn on the
world market and a high exchange rate, Tan said.
</P>
<P>
The government approved last month the import of more rice and
corn for fears of a rice and corn shortage as a result of a severe
drought brought about by the El Nino weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
El Nino has begun to affect the country since the last quarter
of 1997, leading to water shortages in many parts of the country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
