<HEADLINE> CSKA Moscow Rally Back to Win Away Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- CSKA Moscow took a crucial step
towards classification for the next round of the men's Euroleague
Championship after ralling to win over Spain's Estudiantes for
their first away victory on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian side trailed by 11 points before the break, but
bounced back to score a 85-78 victory.
</P>
<P>
The Spaniards lost their momentum after Russian coach Stanislav
Eremin called a time-out and the visitors overtook the lead 63-62
at the end of a crucial three-minute spell.
</P>
<P>
CSKA improved their rebound work and hit a series of
three-pointers to run out easy winners despite seeing both Marcus
Webb and Valery Daimeko fouled out with over five minutes from
time.
</P>
<P>
CSKA were 7-5 from their 12 matches while Estudiantes slipped
to 6-6.
</P>
<P>
In Athens, Champions Olympiakos beat Croatia Split 90-79 in a
group E match with an impressive comeback after trailing six
points at halftime on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It took the Greeks five minutes into the second half to find a
way to control the Croats and eventually showed their top class as
Lithuanian power forward Arturas Karnisovas fired up to score 18
of his 25 points, splitting the Croat defence.
</P>
<P>
After 12 games, Olympiakos' record was 9-3 and Croat Split
dropped to 4-8. 
</P>
