<HEADLINE> Illegal Alien Workers in Thailand to Be Repatriated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 300,000 foreigners
working illegally in Thailand will be repatriated within six
months, according to Thai Labor and Social Welfare Minister
Trairong Suwankhiri.
</P>
<P>
The action would start within the next two weeks and agencies
would give Thais those jobs made vacant, Trairong was quoted
Friday by the local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Foreign Ministry will be responsible for the
repatriation while police and soldiers would make the arrests.
</P>
<P>
Illegal workers would be sent to repatriation centers in Chiang
Rai, Tak, Kanchanaburi and Ranong provinces before being
repatriated.
</P>
<P>
Trairong said he would make sure human rights and international
laws are not violated.
</P>
<P>
The National Security Council has also agreed to plans to
deport illegal alien workers to free up jobs for Thais.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Thais are already jobless and more than 2 million
are expected to be out of work by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of workers from poorer countries in the
region flooded into Thailand during the boom years of the 1980s
and early 1990s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
