<HEADLINE> Canadian Delegation Looks to Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Governor General
Romeo Leblanc and more than 300 Canadian businessmen are in
Brazil for a three-day official visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
There has been trade conflict between Brazil and Canada after
the Canadian Bombardier company stopped a contract for the
purchase 24 Supertucano airliners made in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Brazilian Finance Minister Pedro Malan said the
recent conflict was "an isolated episode" and would not affect
their ties.
</P>
<P>
Malan also briefed the Canadian businessmen the economic
situation in his country, and said he hoped they would increase
investment in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso met with Leblanc
Thursday to discuss bilateral and multilateral interests.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a joint statement that day on
education, human rights, agricultural cooperation, the protection
of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Leblanc and the business delegation arrived here Wednesday
night after visiting Mexico. The delegation will also visit
Argentina and Chile.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian governor general will continue his visit to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Canada exported 980 million U.S. dollars worth of goods to
Brazil and imported 770 million dollars worth of goods and
services last year. It is the ninth biggest foreign investor in
Brazil with nearly 2.8 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
