<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans New Breakthroughs in Modern Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China is planning new
breakthroughs in establishing a modern financial system and a
sound financial order, according to the country's top banking
official.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China (PBOC),
or the central bank, told a press conference held here this
morning, that China this year will implement the principles
mapped out in the recent national financial conference, continue to
adapt a relatively tight monetary policy, strengthen risk-control
on financial enterprises so as to effectively prevent and resolve
risks.
</P>
<P>
Dai noted that China plans to reform the management system of
PBOC, transform the state-owned commercial banks and the People's
Insurance Company of China Group into full-fledged commercial
entities, and develop other types of local financial organs.
</P>
<P>
All financial enterprises are urged to run in accordance with
the law free from the interference from any individual and
department on their operations, Dai said, adding that the
enterprises should also be accountable to their own liabilities
and risks.
</P>
<P>
All state-owned national financial enterprises should set up
supervisory boards, he said.
</P>
<P>
Credit ceiling control imposed by on state-owned commercial
banks will be removed and asset liability ratio management and
risk management will be introduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country will also make efforts to revise the loan loss
provisioning and write-off mechanism. "All banks should improve
the capital replenishment system to raise capital adequacy," Dai
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
