<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Forex Reserve Hits 140 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign exchange
reserve hit a record high of 139.9 billion U.S. dollars by the end
of last year in spite of the financial crisis in Asian emerging
industrial countries.
</P>
<P>
The figure was 34.9 billion U.S. dollars more than a year ago,
Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, told a press conference here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of Renminbi, China's legal tender, rose
steadily by a total of 186 base points to 8.2796 yuan against one
U.S. dollar throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
"The banking sector has witnessed a smooth development in 1997
and played an important role in facilitating economic growth and
safeguarding social stability," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
China will strive to maintain a favorable balance of
international payments and continue to stabilize the exchange rate
of Renminbi in the year 1998, Dai said.  
</P>
