<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, Russia to Enhance Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic said Thursday that his country will further develop
relations with Russia, Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
The economic cooperation between Yugoslavia and Russia had made
remarkable achievements, with the trade volume last year reaching
one billion U.S. dollars, said Milosevic while meeting with
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasyevsky.
</P>
<P>
The two agreed that Yugoslavia had made active and constructive
contributions to peace and stability in Bosnia as well as to the
implementation of the Dayton peace accord, which was signed in
December, 1995 and ended three-and-half-year war in the region,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to further strengthen the functions of the
elected agencies in Bosnia and to maintain peace and stability in
the Bosnian Serb Republic by political means.
</P>
<P>
Afanasyevsky, who is in charge of European affairs, said Russia
supported Yugoslavia's efforts in realizing peace in the region
and smoothly developing the country.
</P>
<P>
Russia is opposed to internationalizing the internal affairs of
Yugoslavia, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
