<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Killed in Renewed Clash in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Four rebels and one soldier were
killed in a clash between the Philippine government troops and the
rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) Thursday in southern
Mindanao island, local press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Maj. Rosque Garingalao, spokesman of an army division based in
Cotabato Province, was quoted as saying the MILF rebels fired 12
rounds of mortar shells at a government post, killing the soldier.
</P>
<P>
Government troops fired back with artillery rounds and two
helicopter gunships rained rockets on the rebel positions in
Buldon City in Cotabato, leaving four rebel fighters dead, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Garingalao said an unknown number of rebels could have been
wounded in the three-hour duel.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of mortar and artillery fire was the first clash
between the government troops and the MILF since a cease-fire was
reached in October 1997 to pave the way for further exploratory
peace talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the renewed conflict might affect the next
round of exploratory talks in February, which are expected to
discuss the agenda for reaching a preliminary peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-MILF peace talks, starting in January 1997, have
been on-and-off due to sporadic fighting between the two forces.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has refused to be included in a peace treaty that the
government signed with the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF)
in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the MNLF, wants a separate
peace agreement with the government.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated 12,000 fighters, the MILF is the largest
anti-government force in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
