<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Help Displaced Workers Find New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Labor will
launch a job training program for the country's estimated 10
million laidoffs in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The program is to help the unemployed people find new jobs by
improving their work skills, Li Boyong, Minister of Labor, was
quoted as saying by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
One important measure contained in the program will be setting
up "re-employment funds" in various places.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers from the sectors such as textile, military
projects, machinery manufacturing and coal mining will have
priority to participate in the training program.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor plans to increase re-employment in
northwest, northeast and southwest China, "especially the
northeast areas, where many large, middle-sized and out-dated
state-owned enterprises are located," told Li.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in China's urban areas remained at three
percent during the first nine months in 1997, according to data
from the Ministry of Labor. Meanwhile, some 5.3 million people had
registered as unemployed by the end of September, down 3.6 percent
from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The nation-wide re-employment project has helped 2.3 million
laidoffs return to work after receiving occupational training and
unemployment relief during the first nine months last year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor will speed up building a labor
information network to provide accurate and timely information for
both employees and job hunters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
