<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Banking Sector Sees Smooth Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China's banking sector has
experienced a steady development in the year 1997 although
financial crisis has hit some other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The balance of aggregate deposits hit 8,240 billion yuan by the
end of last year, up 18.6 percent from a year ago, Dai Xianglong,
governor of the People's Bank of China, the central bank, said at
a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, outstanding bank loans chalked up an increase of
16.7 percent to reach 7,490 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The broad money (M2) and currency in circulation (M0) expanded by
17.3 percent and 15.6 percent, respectively, Dai said.
</P>
<P>
"In general, the money supply was in conformity with the growth
of the economy and the change of prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
China's economic growth kept at 8.8 percent last year and its
retail price index rose just one percent.
</P>
<P>
"The banking sector has played an important role in promoting
economic development and social stability in 1997," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country's foreign exchange reserve hit a
record high of 139.9 billion U.S. dollars by the end of last year,
34.9 billion U.S. dollars more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of Renminbi, China's legal tender, rose
steadily by a total of 186 base points to 8.2796 yuan against the
U.S. dollar throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor told the press that China will strive
to maintain a favorable balance of international payments and
continue to stabilize the exchange rate of Renminbi in the year
1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
