<HEADLINE> Goalkeeper Zenga Announces Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Walter Zenga, Italian goalie
for his national team in the 1990 World Cup who currently served
for the New England Revolution in the U.S. Major League Soccer,
announced his retirement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Revolution officials tried to negotiate a contract
extension, but the 37-year-old Zenga wanted to return home to
Milan.
</P>
<P>
"This decison was one of the hardest of my life," said Zenga.
"But I miss my family in Italy and I need to think about my career
after soccer."
</P>
<P>
The veteran Zenga played for Italy's first divison for 11 years
and had 38 shutouts in 58 appearances with Italy.
</P>
<P>
He starred for Internazionale of Milan and played for Sampdoria
of Genoa later. His last appearance for Italy was in a 2-0 win
over Ireland at Foxboro Stadium in June 1992.
</P>
<P>
Zenga missed nine games last season while recovering from
arthroscopic surgery. The Revolution lost all nine games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
