<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Financed Project Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The largest environmental
protection project in central and west China has officially
started in northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Costing 2.55 billion yuan (307 million US dollars) of which 156
million US dollars will be loaned by the Asian Development Bank,
the project is aimed at fighting air pollution in Xi'an, Xianyang,
and Tongchuan in Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
Due to the reliance of coal for industry and heating, the three
cities have long been suffering from severe air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The project, expected to be completed in 2001, include three
central heating projects, two natural supply projects, and a
cement fly ash treatment project.
</P>
<P>
The first ADB-financed environmental protection project is
designed to replace 515 polluted small boilers, provide piped
natural gas to 130,000 urban families, save 844,000 tons of coal a
year, thus remarkably reduce air pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0346 </DOCNO>
