<HEADLINE> EU to Investigate Belgian F1 Complaint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Thursday that it would investigate a complaint against the
International Automobile Federation (FIA) for threatening to
cancel the Belgian Formula One Grand Prix race.
</P>
<P>
A source close to European Union competition commissioner Karel
van Miert said that the commissioner would consider the complaint
and analyze it seriously.
</P>
<P>
The complaint was filed by some 60 Formula One enthusiasts,
some of whom are cafe and restaurant holders near the Spa
Francorchamps race track.
</P>
<P>
FIA said on Wednesday that it gave the organizers of the
Belgian Formula One race until February 15 to give guarantees that
the country's ban on tobacco sponsorship and advertising would not
affect the race.
</P>
<P>
Spa Francorchamps is still one of this year's stops on the FIA
circuit but FIA said that the race could be scrapped from next
year's calendar when the new Belgian law banning tobacco
advertising enters into force on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
A local court in the Belgian province of Wallonia has already
ruled that it was powerless to suspend the government ban to bring
it in line with the more lenient EU legislation.
</P>
<P>
The European Union decided to phase out most tobacco
advertising within three years but would give tobacco sponsorship
of events such as the Formula One races until 2006.
</P>
<P>
Representing the Spa Francorchamps enthusiasts is lawyer
Jean-Louis Dupont who successfully helped Belgian soccer player
Jean-Marc Bosman winning his case in the European Court of
Justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
