<HEADLINE> Former Olympic Champion Wins Doping Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Daniel Plaza of Spain, the
20-kilometer walk champion in the 1992 Olympics, won his appeal to
compete again despite his positive results for steroid, local
reports said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Plaza was free to compete again after a Madrid court halted his
suspension for doping pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
In October, Spain's Sport Disciplinary Committee suspended
Plaza for two years for his positive results for steroid
nandrolone on June 28, 1996, just before the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
He tested negative in two subsequent tests prior to Atlanta and
was allowed to enter the games.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy about the decision because it shows that there
are enough reasons to doubt the committee's decision and to back
my innocence," Plaza said.
</P>
<P>
Plaza won the 20K event in Barcelona in 1992 but finished 11th
in Atlanta. 
</P>
