<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., EU Promote Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
European Union (EU) concluded a one-day ministerial meeting here
today for promoting the trans-Atlantic relations soured since the
end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary Madeleine Albright, British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook and Vice President Sir Leon Brittan of the European
Commission discussed a series of issues ranging from Turkey-EU
relations, the Middle East and Bosnia peace process
</P>
<P>
"The primary purpose of our meeting today, however, was to
discuss the relationship between the United States and the
European Union," Albright told a press conference after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Those ties are a central part of a broader new Atlantic
community that includes NATO, the OSCE (Organization on Security
and Cooperation in Europe) and other transatlantic organizations,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
"As the United Kingdom begins its six- month term as EU
president, Europe and the United States have an opportunity and a
responsibility to lead in a range of areas where, if we don't show
the way, no one else can or will," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, the three discussed how to sustain the
Middle East peace process, promote reconciliation in Bosnia and
combat climate change.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed the importance of strong transatlantic
leadership on trade and economic affairs, according to Albright.
</P>
<P>
Cook indicated that transatlantic dialogue is "of great
importance" on fighting jobless, crime and the climate change.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, Cook said both sides
recognized the "frustrating stalemate," expressing EU's full
support for the talks brokered by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the U.S. and EU have become sour both in
trade and security after the Cold War ended as the trans-Atlantic
alliance's common adversary, the Soviet Union, disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between the two sides on a U.S. anti-Cuba law is
still in an impasse while their row over the control of NATO's
southern command is still unsettled.
</P>
<P>
Brussels opposes the Helms-Burton Law which sanctions any
foreign firms which do business with Cuba. Paris insisted that the
alliance's southern commander should be a European but the idea
was rejected by Washington.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of trade, Brittan said that "there are bound to be
conflicts," but hen stressed that "we have a commitment to resolve
those problems."
</P>
<P>
On the Helms-Burton Law dispute, Brittan indicated that the
two sides will continue to negotiate based on the understanding
they reached last April. "We need agreement in order to avoid
having to return to the WTO (World Trade Organization)." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
