<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Mixed in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar finished mixed
Thursday, dropping below 130 Japanese yen for the first time in
two weeks after Indonesia agreed to an overall reform package.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose against the German mark, however, on rumors
that Germany might rethink its entry into the planned European
common currency.
</P>
<P>
Against the yen, the dollar also was weakened by a major report
in Japan that Tokyo will devise another economic stimulus package
in March.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 129.81 yen,
down from 130.92 late Wednesday. It was the first finish below 130
yen since December 29 for the dollar, which has lost 3 percent of its
value vs. the yen since hitting a 5-year high on January 5.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency also settled at 1.8318 marks, up from 1.8218.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6303 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6289 U.S. dollars
</P>
<P>
