<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Congress to Act on Tobacco Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
referring to new evidence that the tobacco industry targeted
teenagers, Thursday urged Congress to pass anti-tobacco
legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
Clinton cited reports that the nation's second-largest
cigarette company, R.J. Reynolds, had developed aggressive
marketing proposals to reach adolescents as young as 14.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "The documents that came to light today show more
than ever why it is absolutely imperative that Congress take
action now to get tobacco companies out of the business of
marketing cigarettes to children."
</P>
<P>
The company's internal documents, covering 1973 to 1990, show
it tried to target teens to reverse declining sales of its brands.
</P>
<P>
The president said, "I am confident that every member of
Congress, without regard to party, who reviews these documents
will resolve to make 1998 the year that we actually pass
comprehensive legislation to protect our children and the public
health."  
</P>
</TEXT>
