<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baltics Regard Charter with U.S. A Step to NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting leaders of the
three Baltic nations said here today that the charter to be signed
on Friday with Washington was an important step toward joining the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference, Presidents Lennart Meri,
Guntis ULmanis and Algirdas Brazuskas of Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuania said that the charter moves their countries "closer to
NATO" but is not targeted against Russia.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a substitute for NATO membership. On the contrary,
the charter is moving us closer to NATO," Estonia's Meri said.
</P>
<P>
"It clearly states the United States' policy agenda on the
strategic issues -- the security of the Baltic region and
Europeans a whole," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meri said the Baltic states' application to join NATO, which is
fiercely opposed by Moscow and has been shelved by the alliance
until an undetermined future date, was "the next big challenge to
NATO."
</P>
<P>
"Allies and partners, like NATO and Russia, do not need a band
of neutral states to stand in between them," Meri said.
</P>
<P>
The Estonian president recalled that Russia had first opposed,
and later acquiesced to, NATO's offer last July of membership to
Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary. Russia itself signed a
charter with NATO last May.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania's Brazauskas said: "We all understand the U.S.-
Baltic charter is not directed against a third country or third
country groups."
</P>
<P>
Latvia's Ulmanis added, "I think that our relations with the
USA transcend the boundaries of the partnership concept. We are
becoming allies, allies in the new, broader meaning of the next
millenium."
</P>
<P>
"The charter points to the U.S.'s true interest in the
independence and sovereignty of the Baltic states," said Ulmanis.
"It defines a resolution to facilitate the further inclusion of
the Baltic states in European and trans-Atlantic organization."
</P>
<P>
Reports quoted the charter as saying that the United States
will provide help to the three states to join NATO but will not
guarantee the membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980116.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Approves 40 Million U.S. Dollar Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the approval of financing
equivalent to 40 million U.S. dollars for two projects in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The financing include a 10 million dollar loan for Cashbank, a
bank established in 1995 by a non-governmental organization, the
Group Credit Company, to serve the needs and expand lending
activities for low-income communities within South Africa through
the provision of savings facilities as well as credit for housing,
education, and personal loans.
</P>
<P>
It also includes financing amounting to 30 million dollars
equivalent for Unicell Paper Mills (Pty) Limited, to install and
operate an integrated tissue paper mill in Germiston.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and also the largest
multilateral source of equity and loan financing for private
sector projects in developing countries. IFC opened an office in
Johannesburg in 1994. Up to now, the IFC has approved financing of
100.3 million dollars for 18 projects in South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
